17\">\n{{cite newspaper |last=Williams |first=Jennifer |title=Gary Neville and 'Class of 92' are Opening a University |date=20 September 2017 |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/gary-neville-class-92-opening-13646548 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |access-date=18 November 2017 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NHLE\">\n{{National Heritage List for England |num=1391923 |desc=Trafford Town Hall |access-date=2 December 2012 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OfstedStretfordGrammar\">{{cite web |title=Stretford Grammar School |publisher=Ofsted |date=22 April 2015 |url=https://files.api.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2478507 |format=PDF |access-date=18 November 2017 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ProfileLongford\">\n{{cite web |title=Longford Ward Profile |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/cme/live/dynamic/DocMan2Document.asp?document_id=A919395C-7114-4A39-9FC3-A7B714E51ED0 |access-date=8 May 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930153804/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/cme/live/dynamic/DocMan2Document.asp?document_id=A919395C-7114-4A39-9FC3-A7B714E51ED0 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RBHS\">\n{{cite web |title=Archive of the Royal Botanical and Horticultural Society of Manchester and the Northern Counties |publisher=The Archives Hub |url=https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/search/archives/26cc1435-89eb-386a-b70c-2f2ceec64d84 |access-date=18 November 2017 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"St Ann's\">\n{{NHLE |desc=Church of St Ann |num=1356519 |accessdate=12 August 2007 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"St Matthew\">\n{{NHLE |desc=Church of St Matthew |num=1356518 |accessdate=12 August 2007 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"StretfordStMatthew\">\n{{cite web |title=Stretford, Lancashire |work=A Vision of Britain Through Time |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/985 |access-date=10 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TownshipsStretford\">\n{{citation |title=Townships: Stretford |work=A History of the County of Lancaster |volume=4 |year=1911|pages=329\u201335 |publisher=British History Online |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41436 |access-date=7 April 2007}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TraffordMBC\">\n{{cite web |title=Advertising in Trafford |publisher=Trafford Borough Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/business/advertisingandsponsorship/advertising |access-date=7 August 2012 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015001257/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/business/advertisingandsponsorship/advertising/ |archivedate=15 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Trams\">\n{{cite web |title=Metrolink: Tram Stops: Stretford |url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/metrolink/stops/Stretford |publisher=TheTrams.co.uk |access-date=2 December 2012 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{citation |first=Don |last=Bayliss |year=1996 |title=Historical Atlas of Trafford |publisher=Don Bayliss |isbn=0-9529300-0-5}}\n*{{citation |first=D. A. |last=Farnie |title=John Rylands of Manchester |year=1993 |publisher=John Rylands University Library of Manchester |isbn=0-86373-116-3}}\n*{{citation |last=Gray |first=Edward |title=The Manchester Carriage and Tramways Company |year=1977 |publisher=Manchester Transport Museum Society}}\n*{{citation |last=Greater Manchester Police |title=The Police! 150 Years of Policing in the Manchester Area |publisher=Archive Publications |year=1989 |isbn=0-948946-49-0}}\n*{{citation |first=Samuel |last=Massey |title=A History of Stretford |publisher=John Sherratt and Son |year=1976 |isbn=0-85427-046-9}}\n*{{citation |first1=Vicki |last1=Masterson |last2=Cliff |first2=Karen |title=Stretford: An Illustrated History |publisher=The Breedon Books Publishing Company |year=2002 |isbn=1-85983-321-7}}\n*{{citation |first=Mike |last=Nevell |year=1997 |title=The Archaeology of Trafford |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough with [[Manchester University|University of Manchester Archaeological Unit]] |isbn=1-870695-25-9}}\n*{{citation |first=Robert |last=Nicholls |title=Curiosities of Greater Manchester |publisher=Sutton Publishing |year=2004 |isbn=0-7509-3661-4}}\n*{{citation |first=Robert |last=Nicholls |title=Trafford Park: The First Hundred Years |publisher=Phillimore & Co |year=1996 |isbn=1-86077-013-4}}\n*{{citation |last1=Nicolaisen |first1=W. F. H. |last2=Gelling |first2=M. |last3=Richards |first3=M. |title=The Names of Towns and Cities in Britain |publisher=B. T. Batsford Ltd |year=1970 |isbn=0-7134-0113-3 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/namesoftownsciti0000nico }}\n*{{citation |first=John J. |last=Parkinson-Bailey |title=Manchester: An Architectural History |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=2000 |isbn=0-7190-5606-3}}\n*{{citation |first=Douglas |last=Rendell |year=1998 |title=Cinemas of Trafford |publisher=Jarvis Print Group |isbn=0-9512560-1-7}}\n*{{citation |first=Roger |last=Scola |year=1992 |title=Feeding the Victorian City: the food supply of Manchester, 1770\u20131870 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=0-7190-3088-9}}\n*{{citation |last=Smith |first=Peter J. C. |title=Luftwaffe over Manchester: The Blitz Years 1940\u20131944 |year=2003 |publisher=Neil Richardson |isbn=978-1-85216-151-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Stretford, Greater Manchester|Stretford}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Stretford-article.ogg|2008-04-12}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e_Ejq_VhYC8 Historical documentary on the Borough of Stretford, including footage of the 1933 Charter Day celebrations]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027040207/http://www.geocities.com/larwilson2001/history_of_stretford.htm History of Stretford]\n\n{{Greater Manchester}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Stretford| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Geography of Trafford]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the town in Greater Manchester|the village in Herefordshire|Stretford, Herefordshire}}\n{{distinguish|Stratford (disambiguation){{!}}Stratford}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                  = England\n| coordinates              = {{coord|53.4466|-2.3086|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name            = Stretford\n| population               = 46,910\n| population_ref           = &nbsp;([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011&nbsp;Census]])\n| population_density       = {{convert|9158|/sqmi|/km2|abbr=on}}\n| metropolitan_borough     = [[Trafford]]\n| metropolitan_county      = [[Greater Manchester]]\n| region                   = North West England\n| constituency_westminster = [[Stretford and Urmston (UK Parliament constituency)|Stretford and Urmston]]\n| post_town                = MANCHESTER\n| postcode_area            = M\n| postcode_district        = M32\n| dial_code                = 0161\n| os_grid_reference        = SJ795945\n| london_distance          = {{convert|163|mi|km|0|abbr=on}}&nbsp;[[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n| static_image_name        = Trafford-town-hall3.jpg\n| static_image_alt         = Red brick building with central square clock tower.\n| static_image_caption     = [[Trafford Town Hall]] in Stretford\n}}\n'''Stretford''' is a town in [[Trafford]], Greater Manchester, England, on flat ground between the [[River Mersey]] and the [[Manchester Ship Canal]],  {{convert|3.8|mi|km|1}} southwest of [[Manchester city centre]], {{convert|3.0|mi|km|1}} south of [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]] and {{convert|4.2|mi|km|1}} northeast of [[Altrincham]]. Stretford borders [[Chorlton-cum-Hardy]] to the east, [[Urmston]] to the west, Salford to the north, and [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]] to the south. The [[Bridgewater Canal]] bisects the town.\n\n[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in [[Lancashire]], in the 19th century Stretford was an agricultural village, known locally as Porkhampton due to the large number of pigs produced for the Manchester market. It was also an extensive market-gardening area, producing more than {{convert|500|LT|sigfig=3}} of vegetables each week for sale in Manchester by 1845. The arrival of the Manchester Ship Canal in 1894, and the subsequent development of the [[Trafford Park]] industrial estate, accelerated the industrialisation that had begun in the late 19th century. By 2001 less than one per cent of Stretford's population was employed in agriculture.\n\nStretford has been the home of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United Football Club]] since 1910, and of [[Lancashire County Cricket Club]] since 1864. Notable residents have included the industrialist, philanthropist, and Manchester's first multi-millionaire [[John Rylands]], the [[suffragette]] [[Emmeline Pankhurst]], the painter [[L. S. Lowry]], [[Morrissey]], [[Joy Division]] frontman [[Ian Curtis]] and [[Jay Kay]] of [[Jamiroquai]].\n\n==History==\nThe origin of the name Stretford is \"street\" ([[Old English]] ''str\u00e6t'') on a ford across the [[River Mersey]].{{sfnp|Nicolaisen|Gelling|Richards|1970|p=177|ps=none}} The principal road through Stretford, the [[A56 road|A56 Chester Road]], follows the line of the old [[Roman road]] from [[Deva Victrix]] ([[Chester]]) to [[Mamucium]] ([[Manchester]]), crossing the Mersey into Stretford at Crossford Bridge, built at the location of the ancient ford.{{r|TownshipsStretford}}\nThe earliest evidence of human occupation around Stretford comes from [[Neolithic]] stone axes found in the area, dating from about 2000&nbsp;BC. Stretford was part of the land occupied by the [[Celts|Celtic]] [[Brigantes]] tribe before and during the Roman occupation, and lay on their border with the [[Cornovii (Midlands)|Cornovii]] on the southern side of the Mersey.{{sfnp|Bayliss|1996|p=6|ps=none}} By 1212, there were two [[manorialism|manors]] in the area now called Stretford. The land in the south, close to the River Mersey, was held by [[Hamon de Massey|Hamon de Mascy]], while the land in the north, closer to the [[River Irwell]], was held by Henry de Trafford.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=12|ps=none}} In about 1250, a later Hamon de Mascy gave the Stretford manor to his daughter, Margery. She in turn, in about 1260, granted Stretford to Richard de Trafford at a rent of one penny. The de Mascy family shortly afterwards released all rights to their lands in Stretford to Henry de Trafford, the Trafford family thus acquiring the whole of Stretford, since when the two manors descended together.{{r|TownshipsStretford}}\n\nThe de Trafford family leased out large parts of the land, much of it to tenants who farmed at subsistence levels. Although there is known to have been a papermill operating in 1765, the area remained largely rural until the early 20th-century development of [[Trafford Park]] in the Old Trafford district north of the town.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=13|ps=none}} Until then Stretford \"remained in the background of daily life in England\",{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=15|ps=none}} except for a brief cameo role during the [[Jacobite rising of 1745]], when Crossford Bridge was destroyed to prevent a crossing by [[Charles Edward Stuart|Bonnie Prince Charlie]]'s army during its abortive advance on London; the bridge was quickly rebuilt.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=15|ps=none}}\n\nUntil the 1820s one of Stretford's main cottage industries was the hand-weaving of cotton. There were reported at one time to have been 302&nbsp;handlooms operating in Stretford, providing employment for 780 workers, but by 1826 only four were still in use, as the mechanised cotton mills of nearby Manchester replaced handlooms.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=38|ps=none}} As Manchester continued to grow, it offered a good and easily accessible market for Stretford's agricultural products, in particular [[rhubarb]], once known locally as Stretford beef.{{sfnp|Massey|1976|pp=39, 57|ps=none}} By 1836 [[market gardening]] had become so extensive around Stretford that one writer described it as the \"garden of Lancashire\";{{sfnp|Scola|1992|p=97|ps=none}} in 1845 more than 500&nbsp;tons of vegetables were being produced for the Manchester market each week.{{sfnp|Scola|1992|p=105|ps=none}} Stretford also became well known for its pig market and the production of [[black pudding]]s, leading to the village being given the nickname of Porkhampton. A local dish, known as Stretford goose, was made from pork stuffed with sage and onions. During the 1830s, between 800 and 1,000 pigs a week were being slaughtered for the Manchester market.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|pp=19\u201320|ps=none}}\n\nSituated on the border with Manchester, Stretford became a fashionable place to live in the mid-19th century.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=23|ps=none}} Large recreation areas were established, such as the Royal Botanical Gardens, opened in 1831. The gardens were sited in Old Trafford on the advice of scientist [[John Dalton]], because the prevailing southwesterly wind kept the area clear of the city's airborne pollution.{{r|RBHS}} In 1857, the gardens hosted the [[Art Treasures Exhibition]], the largest art exhibition ever held in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester 1857, a City of Industry |publisher=Manchester Art Gallery |url=http://www.manchestergalleries.org/whats-on/art-treasures-in-detail/manchester-1857/ |access-date=16 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref> A purpose-built iron and glass building was constructed at a cost of \u00a338,000 to house the 16,000&nbsp;exhibits.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=107|ps=none}} The gardens were also chosen as a site for the [[Royal Jubilee Exhibition, Manchester 1887|Royal Jubilee Exhibition]] of 1887, celebrating [[Queen Victoria]]'s 50-year reign. The exhibition ran for more than six&nbsp;months and was attended by more than 4.75&nbsp;million visitors.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|pp=107\u2013110|ps=none}} The gardens were converted into an entertainment resort in 1907, and hosted the first speedway meeting in Greater Manchester on 16 June 1928.<ref>{{cite web |title=White City Track |publisher=UK Running Track Directory |url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=manchester-wc |access-date=9 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref> There was also greyhound racing from 1930, and an athletics track. The complex was demolished in the late 1980s, and all that remains is the entrance gates, close to what is now the White City Retail Park. The gates were designated a Grade II [[listed building|listed structure]] in 1987.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Entrance Portal and Lodges to Former White City Greyhound Track |num=1067874 |accessdate=9 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n===Industrialisation===\nThe arrival of the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] in 1894, and the subsequent development of the Trafford Park industrial estate in the north of the town&nbsp;\u2013 the first planned industrial estate in the world{{sfnp|Nicholls|1996|p=xiii|ps=none}}&nbsp;\u2013 had a substantial effect on Stretford's growth. The population in 1891 was 21,751, but by 1901 it had increased by 40% to 30,436 as people were drawn to the town by the promise of work in the new industries at Trafford Park.<ref>{{cite web |title=1901 Census of England and Wales |work=A Vision of Britain Through Time |publisher=Great Britain Historical GIS Project |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/census/table_page.jsp?tab_id=EW1901COU_M12&u_id=10075592&show=DB&min_c=1&max_c=5  |access-date=12 July 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref>{{sfnp|Nevell|1997|p=24|ps=none}}\n\nDuring the Second World War Trafford Park was largely turned over to the production of [[mat\u00e9riel]], including the [[Avro Manchester]] heavy bomber, and the [[Rolls-Royce Merlin]] engines used to power both the [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] and the [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster]].{{sfnp|Nicholls|1996|pp=103\u2013104|ps=none}}{{efn|The Rolls-Royce Merlin engine was made by Ford, under licence. The factory produced 34,000&nbsp;engines, and employed 17,316&nbsp;people.{{sfnp|Nicholls|1996|pp=103\u2013104|ps=none}}}} That resulted in Stretford being the target for heavy bombing, particularly during the [[Manchester Blitz]] of 1940. On the nights of 22/23 and 23/24 December 1940 alone, 124&nbsp;incendiaries and 120&nbsp;high-explosive bombs fell on the town, killing 73 people and injuring many more. Among the buildings damaged or destroyed during the war were [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford football ground]], All Saints' Church,<ref>{{cite web |title=All Saints Church |work=Trafford Lifetimes |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=2630 |access-date=2 August 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191603/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=2630 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> St Hilda's Church,<ref>{{cite web |title=St. Hilda's church showing bomb damage |work=Trafford Lifetimes |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=2403 |access-date=2 August 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191836/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=2403 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the children's library in King Street.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bomb damage to the children's library, King Street |work=Trafford Lifetimes |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=5428 |access-date=2 August 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191848/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=5428 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Smoke generators were set up in the north of the town close to Trafford Park in an effort to hide it from enemy aircraft,{{sfnp|Nicholls|1996|p=97|ps=none}} and 11,900 children were evacuated to safer areas in Lancashire, Cheshire, Derbyshire, and Staffordshire, along with their teachers and supervisors.{{sfnp|Smith|2003|p=54|ps=none}} A memorial to those residents who lost their lives in the bombing was erected in Stretford Cemetery in 1948, over the communal grave of the 17&nbsp;unidentified people who were killed in the blitz of December 1940.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=156|ps=none}}\n\nBetween 1972 and 1975, what is now a closed [[B&Q]] store in Great Stone Road was the 3,000-capacity Hardrock Theatre and Village Discoth\u00e8que, hosting some of that period's major artists in their prime. [[Led Zeppelin]], [[David Bowie]], [[Bob Marley]], [[Elton John]], [[Hawkwind]], [[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[Chaka Khan]], [[Curved Air]] and [[Lou Reed]] were amongst those who appeared. [[Tangerine Dream]] was the last band to perform at the Hardrock, on 19 October 1975.<ref name=\"Hardrock\">{{citation |title=Stretford's 'Hardrock' down memory lane |date=3 August 2007 |first=Simon |last=Greenhalgh |publisher=Messenger Newspapers |url=http://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/features/traffordthroughtime/display.var.1594782.0.stretfords_hardrock_down_memory_lane.php |access-date=8 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019010719/http://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/features/traffordthroughtime/display.var.1594782.0.stretfords_hardrock_down_memory_lane.php |archivedate=19 October 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In more recent years, Lancashire Cricket Club's Old Trafford ground, next door, has provided a concert venue for bands such as [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[The Cure]], [[Radiohead]], [[Coldplay]], [[Arctic Monkeys]] and [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]].{{r|LCCCMusic}}\n\n===Transport history===\nStretford's growth was fuelled by the transport revolutions of the 18th and especially the 19th century: the Bridgewater Canal reached Stretford in 1761, and the railway in 1849. The completion of the [[Manchester South Junction and Altrincham Railway]] (MSJAR) in 1849, passing through Stretford, led to the population of the town nearly doubling in a decade, from 4,998 in 1851 to 8,757 by 1861.{{sfnp|Nevell|1997|p=25|ps=none}}\n\nBecause Stretford is situated on the main [[A56 road]] between [[Chester]] and Manchester many travellers passed through the village, and as this traffic increased, more inns were built to provide travellers with stopping places. One of the earliest forms of public transport through Stretford was the [[stagecoach]]; the Angel Hotel, on the present day site of what used to be the Bass Drum public house,<ref>{{cite web |title=Bass Drum |work=Trafford Lifetimes |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=3342 |access-date=11 July 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191548/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=3342 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> was one of the main stopping places for stagecoaches in Stretford, and the Trafford Arms was another.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=40|ps=none}} Horse-drawn omnibuses replaced the stagecoach service through Stretford in 1845.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|pp=36, 40|ps=none}} The [[Manchester Carriage Company]]'s tramway from Manchester to Stretford was built in 1879, terminating at the Old Cock Hotel on the A56 road, next to which a small depot was built to house the cars and horses.{{sfnp|Gray|1977|pp=63\u201365|ps=none}} A 1900 timetable shows that trams left for Manchester every 10&nbsp;minutes between 8:00&nbsp;am and 10:15&nbsp;pm.{{sfnp|Gray|1977|p=122|ps=none}} The horse-drawn trams were replaced with electric trams in 1902,<ref>{{citation |title=Historian reviews 1,000 years of town history |work=Sale and Altrincham Messenger |url=http://archive.thisistrafford.co.uk/2000/1/6/10109.html |access-date=10 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215142911/http://archive.thisistrafford.co.uk/2000/1/6/10109.html |archivedate=15 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and after the Second World War the trams were replaced by buses.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Short History of Road Passenger Transport in Greater Manchester |publisher=Greater Manchester's Museum of Transport |url=http://www.gmts.co.uk/history/history.html |access-date=10 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212070014/http://www.gmts.co.uk/history/history.html |archivedate=12 December 2007 |url-status=dead |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\nThe MSJAR railway line through Stretford was electrified in 1931 and converted to light rail operation in 1992, when it became part of the [[Manchester Metrolink]] tram network. The first Metrolink tram through Stretford ran on 15 June 1992.{{r|Trams}}\n\n==Governance==\n\n===Civic history===\n[[File:Stretford Borough Council arms.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Arms of the former Stretford Municipal Borough Council]]Stretford was part of the ancient [[Manchester (ancient parish)|parish of Manchester]], within the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Lancashire]].{{r|Gazetteer}} Following the [[Poor Law Amendment Act]] of 1834, a national scheme for dealing with the relief of the poor, Stretford joined the [[Chorlton-upon-Medlock|Chorlton]] Poor Law Union in 1837, one of three such unions in Manchester,<ref>{{citation |title=Manchester Archives and Local Studies: A Guide to Poor Law and Workhouse Records |publisher=Manchester City Council |url=http://www.manchester.gov.uk/downloads/PoorLawRecordsGuide.pdf |access-date=9 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104165117/http://www.manchester.gov.uk/downloads/PoorLawRecordsGuide.pdf |archivedate=4 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> before transferring to the [[Barton-upon-Irwell]] Poor Law Union in 1849.{{r|Gazetteer}} In 1867, Stretford Local Board of Health was established, assuming responsibility for the local government of the area in 1868.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|pp=88\u201389|ps=none}} The board's responsibilities included sanitation and the maintenance of the highways, and it had the authority to levy [[Rates (tax)|rates]] to pay for those services. The local board continued in that role until it was superseded by the creation of [[Stretford Urban District|Stretford Urban District Council]] in 1894,{{r|Gazetteer}} as a result of the [[Local Government Act 1894]].\n\nStretford Urban District became the [[Municipal Borough of Stretford]] in 1933,{{r|Gazetteer}} giving it [[borough status in the United Kingdom]]. Stretford Borough Council was granted its [[Coat of arms|arms]] on 20 February 1933. The roses are the red roses of Lancashire, and the lion in the centre represents [[John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster]]. Above the lion are a crossed flail and scythe; the flail comes from the arms of the de Trafford family; the scythe is a reminder of the agricultural history of the area; the thunderbolts above represent the importance of electricity in Stretford's industrial development. The boat at the bottom represents Stretford's links to the sea via the Manchester Ship Canal.<ref name=\"CivicHeraldry\">{{citation |title=Civic Heraldry of England & Wales |url=http://www.civicheraldry.co.uk/lancs_ob.html |access-date=20 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, as a result of the [[Local Government Act 1972]], the Municipal Borough of Stretford was abolished and Stretford has, since 1 April 1974, formed part of the [[Trafford|Metropolitan Borough of Trafford]], in [[Greater Manchester]].{{r|Gazetteer}} Trafford Town Hall&nbsp;\u2013 previously Stretford Town Hall&nbsp;\u2013 is the administrative centre of Trafford.{{r|NHLE}}\n\n===Political representation===\nThe [[Stretford (UK Parliament constituency)|constituency of Stretford]] was created in 1885, and existed until 1997, when it was replaced by the present [[Stretford and Urmston (UK Parliament constituency)|constituency of Stretford and Urmston]]. [[Kate Green]], a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], became the [[Member of Parliament|MP]] at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]], with a majority of 8,935, representing 48.6% of the vote.<ref>{{citation |title=Stretford and Urmston |work=guardian.co.uk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/constituency/1347/stretford-and-urmston |accessdate=7 April 2010}}</ref> She retained the seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 General Election]] with an increased majority of 19,705, which represents 66.8% of the vote. The [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] took 27.0% of the vote, [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] 2.2%, the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] 2.0%, the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] 1.3%, and the [[Christian Party (UK)|Christian Party]] 0.2%.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000979 |title=Stretford & Urmston parliamentary constituency |newspaper=BBC News |access-date=12 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nStretford is one of the four major urban areas in Trafford; the other three are [[Altrincham]], [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]] and [[Urmston]].<ref name=\"TraffordMBC\"/> The area historically known as Stretford, between the River Irwell in the north and the River Mersey in the south, has since 2004 been divided between the Trafford local government [[Ward (politics)|wards]] of [[Clifford (ward)|Clifford]], [[Longford (ward)|Longford]], [[Gorse Hill (ward)|Gorse Hill]], and [[Stretford (ward)|Stretford]]. Each ward is represented by three local councillors, giving Stretford 12 of the 63 seats on Trafford Council. The wards elect in thirds on a [[2007 United Kingdom local elections|four yearly cycle]].{{r|Constitution}} As of the [[2014 Trafford Council election|2014 local elections]], all 12 councillors representing the Stretford area are members of the Labour Party.{{r|2014LocalElection}}\n\n==Geography==\n{{further|Geography of Greater Manchester}}\n{{climate chart|Stretford\n|2|8|70\n|2|8|70\n|3|10|50\n|5|13|63\n|8|16|51\n|10|19|58\n|12|21|54\n|12|21|69\n|10|18|63\n|7|14|88\n|4|10|82\n|2|7|78\n|float=right\n|source=World Weather Online<ref>{{cite web |title=Stretford Weather, United Kingdom Weather Averages |url=http://www.worldweatheronline.com/Stretford-weather-averages/Greater-Manchester/GB.aspx |publisher=World Weather Online |access-date=19 September 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n|clear=both\n}}\nStretford occupies an area of {{convert|4.1|sqmi|km2|1}}, just north of the [[River Mersey]], at {{Coord|53|26|48|N|2|18|31|W|type:city}} (53.4466, \u22122.3086). The area is generally flat, sloping slightly southwards towards the river valley,<ref name=\"TownshipsStretford\" /> and is approximately {{convert|150|ft|m|0}} above sea level at its highest point.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stretford, United Kingdom |work=Global Gazetteer, Version 2.1 |publisher=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc |url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/UK/O6/Stretford.html |access-date=3 December 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref> The most southerly part of Stretford lies within the flood plain of the River Mersey, and so has historically been prone to flooding. A great deal of flood mitigation work has been carried out in the Mersey Valley since the 1970s, with the stretch of the Mersey through Stretford canalised to speed up the passage of floodwater.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mersey Bank Park and the River Mersey |publisher=Mersey Valley Countryside Warden Service |url=http://www.merseyvalley.org.uk/site/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=55&Itemid=77 |access-date=2 July 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928164421/http://www.merseyvalley.org.uk/site/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=55&Itemid=77 |archivedate=28 September 2007 }}</ref> Emergency floodbasins have also been constructed, [[Sale Water Park]] being a prominent local example, lying immediately to the south of Stretford.\n\n[[File:TraffordAreasStretford.png|thumb|left|The [[Metropolitan Borough of Trafford]], highlighting Stretford in red]]\nStretford comprises the local areas of [[Old Trafford (district)|Old Trafford]], Gorse Hill, Trafford Park and [[Firswood]]. Its climate is generally [[temperate]], with few extremes of temperature or weather. The mean temperature is slightly above average for the United Kingdom. Annual rainfall and average amount of sunshine are both slightly below the average for the UK.{{r|Climate01}}\n\nStretford's built environment developed along the A56 road in two separate sections, corresponding to the original two manors. The area in the south, near to the border with Sale, grew around the church of St Matthew&nbsp;\u2013 an old alternative name for the town was Stretford St. Matthew.{{r|StretfordStMatthew}} The northern part of Stretford was centred on Old Trafford, with undeveloped countryside separating them. During the 19th century, the sections merged.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|pp=20\u201321|ps=none}}\n\nThe western terminus of the early medieval linear earthwork [[Nico Ditch]] is in Hough Moss, just to the east of Stretford; it was probably used as an administrative boundary and dates from the 8th or 9th century.{{sfnp|Nevell|1997|pp=40\u201341|ps=none}}{{clear}}\n\n{{Areas of Stretford}}\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 2em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"3\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|'''Stretford Compared'''\n|-\n|'''[[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 UK Census]]'''||'''Stretford'''||'''Trafford'''||'''England'''\n|-\n|Total population||46,910||226,578||53,012,456\n|-\n|Foreign born||22%||11%||14%\n|-\n|White||63%||86%||85%\n|-\n|Asian||21%||8%||8%\n|-\n|Black||8%||3%||4%\n|-\n|Average age||36.0 y||39.3 y||39.3 y\n|-\n|Over 65 years old||12%||16%||16%\n|}\n\nAs at the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 UK census]], the Stretford area [[Ward (politics)|wards]] of Clifford, Gorse Hill, Longford and Stretford had a total population of 46,910 and a population density of 8,907 persons per square mile (3,439 per km\u00b2).{{r|LocalAreaReports}}\n\nStretford residents had an average age of 36 years, younger than the 39.3 Trafford average. For every 100 females, there were 97.8 males. Of all residents, 42% were single (never married): in Trafford, 33% were single. Of the 19,209 households, 33% were one-person households, 56% were married couples with dependent children, and 15% were lone parents with dependent children. Of those aged 16\u201374 in Stretford, 23% had no [[Education in England#Specialist qualifications|academic qualifications]], higher than the 18% in all of Trafford.{{r|LocalAreaReports}}\n\nWith 78% of residents born in the United Kingdom, there is a relatively high proportion of foreign-born residents reported. There is also a high proportion of non-white people, as 63% of residents were recorded as white. The largest minority group was [[British Asian|Asian]], at 21% of the population.{{r|LocalAreaReports}}\n\nIn 1931, 19% of Stretford's population was middle class and 20% working class compared to 14% middle class and 36% working class nationally. The rest of the population was made up of clerical workers and skilled manual workers. By 1971, the middle class in Stretford had declined steadily to 15% whilst the working class had grown to 31% compared to 24% middle class and 26% working class nationally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_SOC&data_cube=N_RGSOC_G&u_id=10186687&c_id=10001043&add=Y |title=Stretford social class |publisher=Vision of Britain |access-date=8 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:70%; border:0; text-align:center; line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"20\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population change in Stretford since 1801\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1801\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1811\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1821\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1831\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1841\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1851\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1861\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1871\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1881\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1891\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1901\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1911\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1939\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 1971\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:navy;\"| 2001\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!  style=\"background:#9cc; color:navy; height:17px;\"| Population\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,477\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1,720\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2,173\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2,463\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 3,524\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 4,998\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 8,757\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 11,945\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 19,018\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 21,751\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 30,436\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 42,496\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 46,535\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 56,791\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 51,929\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 61,874\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 60,364\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 54,316\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 37,455\n|-\n| colspan=\"20\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|<small>'''Source: A Vision of Britain through Time'''</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Stretford MB/UD: Total Population |publisher=A Vision of Britain through Time |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10186687&c_id=10001043&add=N |access-date=5 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stretford USD: Total Population |publisher=A Vision of Britain through Time |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10004871&c_id=10001043&add=N |access-date=5 December 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref>{{sfnp|Nevell|1997|p=87|ps=none}}\n|}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Trafford Park, Greater Manchester.jpg|right|thumb|Entrance to [[Trafford Park]] industrial estate]]\nUntil the end of the 19th century Stretford was a largely agricultural village. The development of the [[Trafford Park]] industrial estate in the north of the town, beginning in the late 19th century, had a significant effect on Stretford's subsequent development. At its peak in 1945 the park employed an estimated 75,000&nbsp;workers;{{sfnp|Nevell|1997|pp=130\u2013133|ps=none}} housing and other amenities had to be constructed on what had previously been agricultural land.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=43|ps=none}} Trafford Park is still a very significant source of employment, containing an estimated 1,400 companies and employing about 44,000 people.<ref name=\"TraffordMBC\"/>\n\nThe main shopping centre is Stretford Mall in the [[central business district|commercial centre]] of Stretford, previously known as Stretford [[Arndale Centre|Arndale]]. It was opened in 1969 and changed its name in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arndale Centre opening |work=Trafford Lifetimes |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=3371 |access-date=10 January 2008 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213212449/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=3371 |archivedate=13 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Stretford Mall was built on the site of the original shopping centre in the former King Street. [[The Trafford Centre]], a large shopping and leisure complex opened in September 1998, lies to the northwest of Stretford. Frequent shuttle buses run between Stretford [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink]] tram station and The Trafford Centre, about {{convert|2.5|mi|km|1}} away.<ref>{{cite web |title=Getting Here |publisher=The Trafford Centre |url=http://www.traffordcentre.co.uk/gettinghere |access-date=26 March 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:StretfordTownCentre.jpg|thumb|left|Stretford's town centre, showing Stretford Mall in the midground]]\nAccording to the 2011 UK census, the industry of employment of residents in Stretford was 17% retail and wholesale, 11% health and social work, 11% education, 7% manufacturing, 6% transport and storage, 6% public administration and defence, 6% professional, scientific and technical activities, 5% hotels and restaurants, 5% construction, 5% finance, 1% energy and water supply, 0.06% agriculture and 5% other.{{r|Employment}} This is roughly in line with national figures, except for the town's relatively low percentage of agricultural workers.\n\nThe 2011 census recorded the economic activity of residents aged 16\u201374 as 39.3% in full-time employment, 13.6% in part-time employment, 7.5% self-employed, 5.7% unemployed, 5.9% students, 9.5% retired, 5.6% looking after home or family, and 6.1% permanently sick or disabled. The 5.7% unemployment rate in Stretford was high compared with the national rate of 3.2%.{{r|EconomicSex}} According to the [[Office for National Statistics]] estimates, between April 2001 and March 2002 the average gross income of households in Stretford was \u00a3415 per week (\u00a321,664 per year).{{r|Income}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Landmarks==\n\n===Longford Cinema===\n[[File:LongfordCinema2007640.jpg|thumb|right|Longford Cinema, May 2007]]\nLongford Cinema, opposite Stretford Mall, on the eastern side of the [[A56 road|A56 Chester Road]], is perhaps the most visually striking building in the town. Designed by the architect Henry Elder, it was the height of [[Art Deco]] fashion when it was opened by the Mayor of Stretford in 1936. Its unusual \"cash register\" frontage was intended to symbolise the business aspect of show business.{{sfnp|Rendell|1998|p=55|ps=none}}\n\nThe building incorporated many modern features, such as sound-proofing and under-seat heating,<ref name=\"LongfordCinema\" /> and it was also the first cinema in Britain to make use of concealed neon lighting. It had a [[seating capacity]] of 1,400 in the stalls and 600 in the circle, with a further 146 seats in the caf\u00e9 area.{{sfnp|Rendell|1998|p=55|ps=none}} When built, the cinema had a short pedestrian approach to the facade, which was removed when the A56 was widened. During the Second World War the building was used for concerts, including one given by a young [[Julie Andrews]].{{r|LongfordCinema}} It also played host to the [[Hall\u00e9 Orchestra]] after the orchestra's own home, the [[Free Trade Hall]], was bombed and severely damaged during the [[Manchester Blitz]] of 1940.\n\nAfter a change of ownership in 1950, the cinema was renamed the Stretford Essoldo. It continued to operate as a cinema until 1965, when it was converted into a [[Bingo (UK)|bingo]] hall, which it remained until its closure in 1995.{{r|LongfordCinema}} The building has been unused since then. It was designated a [[Listed building|Grade II listed]] building in 1994.{{r|LongfordCinemaIOE}}\n\nIn 2017 a proposal was put forward by Trafford Council to bring the Essoldo back into use as part of the new University Academy 92, to provide student amenities and other community facilities such as an enhanced library.{{r|LongfordCinema}}\n\n===Great Stone===\n[[File:GreatStone640.jpg|thumb|right|The Great Stone]]\nThe Great Stone, which gave its name to the Great Stone Road, where it was located until being moved in 1925, is one of Stretford's most easily overlooked landmarks. The stone is composed of [[millstone grit]] and was probably deposited as a [[glacial erratic]]. It is rectangular in shape, about {{nowrap|{{convert|5|ft|m|0}}}} wide, {{nowrap|{{convert|2|ft|m|0}}}} deep, and {{nowrap|{{convert|3|ft|m|0}}}} tall, with two {{convert|7|in|cm|adj=on}} deep rectangular slots cut into its upper surface.\n\nSeveral suggestions have been made for the history of the Great Stone. There was a succession of plagues in Manchester from the 14th century onwards,<ref>{{citation |title=The City and Parish of Manchester |work=A History of the County of Lancaster: Volume 4 |publisher=British History Online |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41404 |access-date=8 January 2008}}</ref> and during the Great Plague of 1655\u201356 the holes in the top of the stone were filled with vinegar or holy water, through which coins were passed in the belief that would halt the spread of the disease.<ref>Nicholls, ''Curiosities of Greater Manchester'', p.&nbsp;86.</ref> But the holes are probably too deep for that to have been the stone's original purpose. It may have been a marker on the Roman road between [[Northwich]] and Manchester, or some kind of boundary marker.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Great Cross, Stretford |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=76747 |publisher=Pastscape.org.uk |access-date=8 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref> The Great Stone is also thought to have been the base of an Anglo-Saxon cross shaft.{{sfnp|Nevell|1997|p=87|ps=none}} A local legend had it that the stone was slowly sinking into the earth, and that its ultimate disappearance would mark the end of the world.{{sfnp|Massey|1976|p=25|ps=none}}\n\nWhen the Great Stone Road was widened in the late 19th century, the stone was moved back from the road slightly. In 1925, the stone was moved again, to its current location outside the North Lodge of Gorse Hill Park, about {{convert|328|ft|m|0}} from its historical location. The stone is a Grade II listed structure.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=The Great Stone Stretford |num=1067875 |accessdate=8 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\n===Cenotaph===\n[[File:Cenotaph640.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A four-sided stone column topped with a lion lying down, in a small semi-circular paved garden area.|Stretford Cenotaph]]\nStretford Cenotaph, opposite the Chester Road entrance to Gorse Hill Park, was built as a memorial to the 580 Stretford men who lost their lives in the First World War. Their names and regiments are listed on a large bronze plaque on the wall behind the cenotaph. It was formally unveiled in 1923, by the [[Edward Stanley, 17th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]], Secretary of State for War.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stretford Cenotaph |work=National Recording Project |publisher=Public Monument and Sculpture Association |url=http://pmsa.cch.kcl.ac.uk/pmsa-database/4641/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922181842/http://pmsa.cch.kcl.ac.uk/pmsa-database/4641/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 September 2013 |access-date=2 December 2012 |mode=cs2 }}</ref>\n\nThe cenotaph is {{convert|24|ft|m|0}} high and {{convert|11|ft|m|0}} wide at its base. It cost \u00a32,000 to build, raised by public subscription and a donation from the Stretford Red Cross. The memorial bears the legend \"They died that we might live\" on one side, and \"In memory of the heroic dead\" on the other. It is a Grade II listed structure.<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Stretford Cenotaph |num=1309483 |accessdate=8 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\nStretford's remembrance parade, which is made up of the Scouting, Girl Guiding and Boys Brigade divisions from the area as well as the cadets finishes here, in a semi-circle around the Cenotaph whilst the public and independent representatives stand on the main road which is closed for the occasion. The march goes from the Metro Club to the Cenotaph and back, with the Boys Brigade Band striking up the music for this event.\n\n===Longford Park===\nFor more information, see [[Longford Park]]\n\n===Stretford Public Hall===\n[[File:Stretford public hall.jpg|right|thumb|alt=Large two-storey detached building|Stretford Public Hall]]\nStretford Public Hall was built in 1878 by [[John Rylands]].{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=83|ps=none}} It was designed by N. Lofthouse and is on the western side of the A56 Chester Road, opposite the Longford Cinema. Stretford's first public lending library was established in the building in 1883.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=118|ps=none}} On the death of Rylands in 1888, his widow placed the building at the disposal of the local authority for a nominal rent, and on her own death in 1908, the building was bought by Stretford Council for \u00a35,000.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=83|ps=none}}\n\nPublic baths were built to the rear of the building, accessed via Cyprus Street.<ref>{{citation |title=Stretford Baths |publisher=Trafford Council |work=Trafford Lifetimes |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=4723 |access-date=7 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930152446/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=4723 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1940 the new Stretford Library was opened on King Street, and the public hall was rendered surplus. The building re-opened in March 1949 as the Stretford Civic Theatre, with a well-equipped stage for the use of local groups. After the Stretford Leisure Centre opened in 1983 now Stretford Sports Village, the Cyprus Street Baths wing fell into disuse, and was demolished. The remainder of the building began to fall into disrepair, despite being designated a Grade II listed structure in 1987,<ref>{{NHLE |desc=Stretford Civic Theatre |num=1067873 |accessdate=6 December 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref> until Trafford Council refurbished and converted the hall to serve as council offices in the mid-1990s. It was re-opened in 1997, once again named Stretford Public Hall.\n\n===Stretford Cemetery===\nStretford Cemetery was designed by John Shaw and opened in 1885. Its chapel is in the [[Decorated style]], designed by architects Bellamy & Hardy, and quite elaborate.<ref>Hartwell, Clare et al. (2004) Lancashire: Manchester and the South-East. New Haven: Yale U P; p. 652</ref> On the western side is a memorial to the casualties of the Second World War and to the east a newer section of the cemetery.\n\n===Trafford Town Hall===\n[[Trafford Town Hall]] stands in a large site at the junction of Talbot Road and Warwick Road, directly opposite the [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground]]. Work on the building, designed by architects [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] of Bolton, began on 21 August 1931.<ref>{{citation |title=Stretford Town Hall |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=4545 |work=Trafford Lifetimes |access-date=7 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930152433/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/content/tca/display_image.asp?ImageID=4545 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe town hall officially came into use as Stretford Town Hall on the granting of Stretford's charter, on 16 September 1933. In 1974, on the formation of the new Trafford Metropolitan Borough, Stretford Town Hall was adopted as the base for the new council and renamed Trafford Town Hall; it was designated a Grade II listed building in 2007.{{r|NHLE}}\n\n===Union Church===\nThe Union Church was formed in 1862, with John Rylands as its patron;{{sfnp|Farnie|1993|p=89|ps=none}} he laid the foundation stone of its building in Edge Lane, close to Longford Park's southern entrance, in 1867. In the latter part of the 20th century the church was converted into office accommodation but by the early 21st century was standing empty. In 2012 it was restored to its original use a church having been bought by the Church of Christ \u2013 Iglesia ni Cristo.\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:StretfordMetrolink.jpg|thumb|right|Stretford Metrolink station]]\n[[Stretford Metrolink station]] is part of the [[Manchester Metrolink]] tram system, and lies on the [[Altrincham]] to [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] line. Trams leave about every six&nbsp;minutes between 7:15 and 18:30, and every 12&nbsp;minutes at other times of the day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tram Times |publisher=Metrolink |url=http://www.metrolink.co.uk/tramtimes/Pages/default.aspx |access-date=2 December 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref> The nearest main line railway station is [[Trafford Park railway station|Trafford Park]], on the Liverpool to Manchester line. Services are roughly every two&nbsp;hours in each direction, with extra services calling during the peak hours.<ref>{{cite web |title=Station Facilities: Trafford Park (TRA) |publisher=National Rail Enquiries |url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/TRA.html |access-date=7 August 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref> The {{nowrap|{{convert|20|acre|ha|0|adj=on}}}} Trafford Park Euroterminal rail freight terminal, opened in 1993, is in the Gorse Hill area of Stretford. It cost \u00a311&nbsp;million and has the capacity to deal with 100,000 containers a year. The containers are handled by two huge gantry cranes, the noise from which has led to complaints from some local residents.{{sfnp|Nicholls|2004|p=161|ps=none}}\n\nThe town has good access to the motorway network. Junction 7 of the [[M60 motorway|M60]] is just to the north of Stretford's boundary with [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], and the [[A56 road]] gives easy access to the south as well as to Manchester city centre in the other direction. Cycle paths exist as part of the Trafford cycle initiative.\n\n[[Manchester Airport]], the busiest in the UK outside London,<ref>{{citation |first=James |last=Wilson |title=A busy hub of connectivity |newspaper=[[Financial Times]]&nbsp;\u2013 FT report&nbsp;\u2013 doing business in Manchester and the NorthWest |publisher=The Financial Times |date=26 April 2007}}</ref> is about {{convert|9|mi|spell=in}} to the south of Stretford. Frequent Bus and Tram services run from Stretford, though taking the Tram will require you to change services at Cornbrook.\n\n==Education==\n{{further|List of schools in Trafford}}\n\nAlong with the rest of Trafford, Stretford maintains a selective education system assessed by the [[11-plus]] examination.\n\n[[File:Stretford High School - geograph.org.uk - 511044.jpg|thumb|left|[[Stretford High School]] in 2007]]\nThe proportion of pupils leaving [[Stretford Grammar School]] with five or more [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]] at grades A*\u2013C in 2006, was 98.3%, compared to an average of 66.7% for all secondary schools in Trafford and a national UK average of 61.3%.{{r|ProfileLongford}} The proportion of students from minority ethnic backgrounds, and for whom English is an additional language, is much higher than the average.{{r|OfstedStretfordGrammar}} Stretford Grammar was awarded specialist [[Science College]] status in September 2005. The school was assessed as \"good\" in its April 2015 [[Office for Standards in Education|Ofsted]] report.{{r|OfstedStretfordGrammar}}\n\nStretford High School Community Languages College, like Stretford Grammar, has a much higher proportion than the national average of pupils with a first language other than English, many of them being either asylum seekers or refugees. In 2004 Stretford High School was made subject to special measures, as it was considered not to be providing an adequate education for its pupils. Substantial improvement has taken place since then; the school was assessed as \"satisfactory\" in its November 2005 Ofsted report and was removed from special measures. Further improvements saw Stretford High School gain an \"outstanding\" assessment from Ofsted, following its February 2008 inspection. GCSE results also placed the school in the top 1% of schools in the country for adding value to its students.<ref name=\"OfstedStretfordHigh\">{{cite web |title=Stretford High School Community Languages College |publisher=Ofsted |date=2 March 2006 |url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_providers/full/(urn)/106370 |access-date=2 September 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\nStretford also has the specialist Arts College, [[Lostock College]].\n\nPlans to build a new university in the town, to be known as University Academy 92, were announced in September 2017. A branch of [[Lancaster University]], it hopes to welcome the first of its anticipated 6500 students in September 2019. The campus is to be built on the Kelloggs headquarters site on Talbot Road, which has already been acquired by Trafford Council for \u00a312 million.{{r|MEN2017}}{{efn|Kelloggs will be moving their offices to [[MediaCityUK]] in 2018.}}\n\n==Religion==\n{{See also|List of churches in Greater Manchester}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" id=\"toc\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 2em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"3\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|'''Stretford Compared'''\n|-\n|'''[[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 UK Census]]'''||'''Stretford'''||'''Trafford'''||'''England'''\n|-\n|Total population||46,910||226,578||53,012,456\n|-\n|Christian||51.2%||63.4%||59.4%\n|-\n|Muslim||18.4%||5.7%||5.0%\n|-\n|Sikh||2.7%||0.7%||0.8%\n|-\n|Hindu||0.8%||1.0%||1.5%\n|-\n|Buddhist||0.3%||0.3%||0.5%\n|-\n|Jewish||0.2%||1.1%||0.5%\n|-\n|No religion||19.7%||21.2%||24.7%\n|}\n\nThe date of the first church to be built in Stretford is unrecorded, but in a lease dated 1413, land is described as lying next to a chapel.{{r|TownshipsStretford}} Many of the present day churches in the area were constructed during the late 19th and early 20th century, as the population of Stretford began to grow.\n\n[[Methodism]] was a significant influence in 19th-century Stretford,{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=11|ps=none}} but of the seventeen churches in the town today, only one is Methodist whereas five are [[Roman Catholic]]. The Catholic mission in Stretford was begun in 1859, in a small chapel on Herbert Street.{{sfnp|Massey|1976|p=126|ps=none}}\n\nAs at the 2011 UK census, 51% of Stretford residents reported themselves as being Christian, 18% as [[Muslim]], and 3% as [[Sikh]]. No other religion was represented at higher than 1% of the population, with 20% reporting themselves as having no religion.\n\nStretford is in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Salford]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Parishes of the Diocese |publisher=Catholic Diocese of Salford |url=http://www.salforddiocese.org.uk/parishes/masstimes.html |access-date=7 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502121806/http://www.salforddiocese.org.uk/parishes/masstimes.html |archivedate=2 May 2007 |url-status=dead |mode=cs2}}</ref> and the [[Anglican Diocese of Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Church of England Diocese of Manchester |url=http://www.manchester.anglican.org/default.asp |access-date=7 May 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227051946/http://www.manchester.anglican.org/default.asp |archivedate=27 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are two [[Listed building|Grade II listed]] churches in Stretford: the Church of [[St Ann's, Stretford|St Ann]]{{r|St Ann's}} and the Church of St Matthew.{{r|St Matthew}} St Ann's is a Roman Catholic church, built in 1862\u201367 by [[E. W. Pugin]] for [[Sir Humphrey de Trafford|Sir Humphrey]] and Lady Annette de Trafford.<ref name=\"St Ann's\"/> It was officially opened by [[William Turner (Bishop of Salford)|Bishop William Turner]] on 22 November 1863, and was [[consecration|consecrated]] in June 1867.{{sfnp|Massey|1976|p=127}} Features include a historic organ built by Jardine & Co (1867) and a good number of fine stained glass windows by Hardman & Co of Birmingham. St Matthew's church was built in 1842 by W. Hayley in the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] style, with additional phases in 1869, 1906 and 1922.<ref name=\"St Matthew\"/>\n\n==Sports==\n\nStretford has been the home of [[Manchester United FC|Manchester United Football Club]] since 1910, when the club moved to its present [[Old Trafford (football)|Old Trafford]] ground, the western end of which is still unofficially called the [[Stretford End]].<ref name=\"Curry\">{{cite news |last1=Curry |first1=Emma |title=Nostalgia: There's more to Old Trafford than football and cricket |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/nostalgia/nostalgia-theres-more-old-trafford-11083905 |accessdate=1 December 2018 |work=men |date=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Old Traford.jpg|thumb|left|Manchester United's Old Trafford football ground]]\n[[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]] was originally the home of [[Manchester Cricket Club]], but became the home of [[Lancashire County Cricket Club]] in 1864 upon that club's formation. The ground is on Talbot Road, Stretford, where it has been since 1856. Similar to its counterpart, one end of the Old Trafford cricket ground is called the Stretford End. It has been a Test venue since 1884 and has hosted three [[Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] semi-finals.<ref name=\"Old Trafford Cricket Ground 150\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/6637911.stm |title=Cricket ground makes 150 not out |publisher=BBC Online |date=9 May 2007 |access-date=23 May 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref> After the 2005 Ashes Test, when more than 20,000 fans had to be turned away,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2006/04/21/210406_ashes_old_trafford_reaction_feature.shtml |title=Ashes to Ashes |publisher=BBC Online |date=21 April 2006 |access-date=23 May 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref> the decision was made to increase the ground's capacity from 20,000 to 25,000. Initial plans included building a new stadium on the site of Trafford Town Hall, opposite the present ground. Trafford Council voted against the demolition of the town hall and instead, in 2007, signed an agreement jointly with Lancashire County Cricket Club, Ask Developments, and [[Tesco]], to redevelop the ground on its present site.<ref name=\"FourWayAgreement\" /> [[File:LCCC Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|Lancashire CCC&nbsp;\u2013 main entrance]] The new cricket ground will be at the heart of a {{convert|750000|sqft|m2|0}} development that will also include business space, residential, retail, hotel and leisure facilities.<ref name=\"FourWayAgreement\">{{cite web |title=Four-way agreement on Old Trafford future |publisher=Lancashire County Cricket Club |url=http://www.lccc.co.uk/index.php?p=news&id=1116 |access-date=16 August 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070218172725/http://www.lccc.co.uk/index.php?p=news&id=1116 |archivedate=18 February 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> More than \u00a325&nbsp;million is expected to be invested in the redevelopments at Old Trafford.<ref name=\"Old Trafford Cricket Ground 150\"/>\n\n[[Stretford Stadium]], adjoining Longford Park, is the home of Trafford Athletic Club. Trafford is one of the UK's top athletic clubs, with more than 100 members having competed at international level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trafford Athletic Club |url=http://www.traffordac.co.uk/ |access-date=26 March 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\nThe Stretford Sports Village run by Trafford Community Leisure Trust comprises two main centres: the original Stretford Leisure Centre, now called the Chester Centre, and the facility at Stretford High School called the Talbot Centre. The Stretford Sports Village is between Manchester United Football Club's Old Trafford Stadium and Lancashire County Cricket Club's Old Trafford Ground. The centres have a 25-metre main pool, a 20-metre children's pool, four gyms, a table tennis room, twelve badminton courts, two [[five-a-side football|five-a-side]] courts, a spinning studio, practice hall, training rooms, community room, a cafe, an outdoor full-size floodlight [[artificial turf]] pitch and a full-size grass pitch.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stretford Sports Village |url=http://www.traffordleisure.co.uk/centres/stretford/ |publisher=Trafford Community Leisure Trust |access-date=24 May 2011 |mode=cs2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521040046/http://www.traffordleisure.co.uk/centres/stretford/ |archive-date=21 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Sale Water Park|Trafford Water Sports Centre]] lies just across Stretford's southern border with Sale, about {{convert|1|mi|spell=in}} from Stretford town centre.\n\n==Culture and cultural references==\nAlthough Stretford town centre is busy during the day, there is very little in the way of a night-time economy.<ref name=\"ProfileStretford\">{{citation |title=Stretford Ward Profile |publisher=Trafford Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/cme/live/dynamic/DocMan2Document.asp?document_id=6C022A5E-3653-424B-AF38-0F34BF8C3228 |access-date=8 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930152409/http://www.trafford.gov.uk/cme/live/dynamic/DocMan2Document.asp?document_id=6C022A5E-3653-424B-AF38-0F34BF8C3228 |archivedate=30 September 2007}}</ref> There are no restaurants or other entertainments except for a number of [[public houses]] and members-only social clubs. There are two public libraries: Greatstone Library, part of Stretford Sports Village, and Stretford Library, both run by Trafford Council.\n\nThe Stretford Pageant is an annual Rose Queen festival held on the last Saturday of June; the inaugural pageant was staged in 1919.{{sfnp|Masterson|Cliff|2002|p=115|ps=none}} There is a procession of decorated floats through the streets, collecting money for local charities and ending at Longford Park, where the Rose Queen is crowned. The tradition of the Rose Queen derives from an earlier event organised by St Peter's Church from 1909 until the pageant began in 1919. Various other entertainments are provided in the park on the day of the pageant, such as a fun fair and a [[car boot sale]]. Stretford Pageant, along with similar events in other parts of Trafford, is under threat because of the council's proposals to reduce funding and support for such events in the future.<ref>{{citation |title=Brassed off over Festival Funding |first=Katherine |last=Vine | work=Manchester Evening News |publisher=Manchester Metro News |date=26 October 2007 |url=http://www.metronews.co.uk/news/s/1021623_brassed_off_over_festival_funding |access-date=17 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Stretford Wives]]'' is a television drama that was broadcast by the BBC in August 2002, watched by 5.7&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{citation |title=Bond shakes off Ripley drama |work=The Guardian|date=22 August 2008 |first=Jason |last=Deans|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/aug/22/overnights |access-date=10 January 2008 |location=London}}</ref> Written by [[Danny Brocklehurst]], it is the story of three sisters living in Stretford, although most of the filming took place in nearby Salford. The programme received a mixed critical reception.<ref>{{citation |title=Stretford Wives |url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b886acaa6 |publisher=British Film Institute |access-date=3 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=In My View&nbsp;\u2013 Stretford Wives |first=Eric |last=Jackson |date=22 August 2002 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/film_and_tv/s/17/17530_in_my_view__stretford_wives.html |access-date=10 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Invention and discovery===\nThe [[Stretford process]] was developed at the North-Western Gas Board's laboratories in Stretford during the 1940s. It was the first liquid phase oxidation process for removing hydrogen sulphide (H<sub>2</sub>S) from [[town gas]] to be commercially successful. Many Stretford plants were built worldwide.<ref>{{citation |last1=Nagl |first1=Gary J |title=The State of Liquid Redox |work=Gas Technology Products |publisher=Merichem Company |year=2005 |url=http://www.merichem.com/resources/technical_papers/state_of_liquid_redox/index.php |access-date=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public services==\nPolicing in Stretford is the responsibility of the [[Greater Manchester Police]], who have their headquarters in the town.<ref>{{citation |title=A History of Greater Manchester Police: 1974\u20132004 |publisher=Greater Manchester Police\n |url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/mainsite/0/1A2F40969DD55F7880257176003AD2C9/$file/GMPHistory74-04.pdf |access-date=28 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202084024/http://www.gmp.police.uk/mainsite/0/1A2F40969DD55F7880257176003AD2C9/%24file/GMPHistory74-04.pdf |archivedate=2 December 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The force's \"M\" Division, responsible for policing in Trafford, is also based in Stretford, close to Trafford Town Hall.{{sfnp|Greater Manchester Police|1989|p=45|ps=none}}\n\n[[Waste management]] is co-ordinated by the local authority via the [[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.gmwda.gov.uk/ |title=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority (GMWDA)|publisher=gmwda.gov.uk|author=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority |year=2008 |access-date=8 February 2008|author-link=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority}}</ref>\n\nHealthcare is overseen by the NHS with hospitals nearby in [[Urmston]] and [[Wythenshawe]]. The nearest Ambulance Stations are located in [[Umsmton]] and [[Sale]].\n\nGreater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service (GMFRS) oversee the Fire and Rescue services in the area here. One of their 3 Fire Stations can be found in Stretford on Park Road, near the Trafford Centre and Kelloggs Factory.\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Westminster emmeline pankhurst statue 1.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph|Statue of Emmeline Pankhurst in [[Victoria Tower Gardens]], [[City of Westminster|Westminster]]]]\nPerhaps fittingly for an area so close to Trafford Park, the world's first planned industrial estate, one of the world's first industrial espionage agents, John Holker, was born in Stretford, in 1719.<ref>{{cite ODNB |title=Holker, John (1719\u20131786) |last=Harris |first=J. R. |year=2004 |edition=online |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/13507?docPos=2 |access-date=10 January 2008|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/13507 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Science and Technology in the Early French Chemical Industry |first=John Graham |last=Smith |publisher=University of Leicester |url=http://www.le.ac.uk/hi/teaching/papers/scitech.html |access-date=11 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Stretford's famous residents were the [[suffragette]] [[Emmeline Pankhurst]] and the painter [[L. S. Lowry]], who was born in Stretford in 1887.<ref>{{cite ODNB |id=31378 |title=Lowry, Joseph Wilson (1803\u20131879) |last1=Levy |first1=Mervyn |last2=(revised by) Spalding |first2=Julian |year=2006 |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/31378 |access-date=10 January 2008 |mode=cs2}}</ref> Manchester's first multi-millionaire [[John Rylands]] and his wife Enriqueta Augustina Rylands lived at Longford Hall in Stretford during the later parts of their lives.<ref>{{cite ODNB |last=Farnie |id=24416 |first=D. A. |title=Rylands, John (1801\u20131888) |year=2004 |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/24416 |access-date=12 February 2018 |mode=cs2}}</ref> The radical firebrand socialist, and later post-war politician [[Herschel Austin|Herschel Lewis Austin]] (1911\u20131974) served Stretford as a Labour Member of Parliament between 1945 and 1950.\n\nSir [[Walter Baldwin Spencer]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]] (1860\u20131929) a British-Australian [[Biology|biologist]] and [[anthropology|anthropologist]] was born in Stretford,<ref>{{cite ODNB |last=Mulvaney |first=D. J. |title=Spencer, Sir (Walter) Baldwin (1860\u20131929) |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36212 |year=2004 |access-date=9 July 2009 |last2=Harrison |first2=B. |edition=online|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/36212 }}</ref> as were [[ABC (band)|ABC]]'s lead singer [[Martin Fry]], [[Rock climbing|rock climber]] [[Derek Hersey]]<ref name=\"Independent\">{{citation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-derek-hersey-1494003.html |newspaper=The Independent |title=Obituary: Derek Hersey |date=26 June 1993 |access-date=5 July 2011}}</ref> and television actor [[John Comer]], best known for his role as caf\u00e9 owner Sid in the BBC sitcom ''[[Last of the Summer Wine]]''.<ref>{{citation |magazine=St Ann's, Stretford Parish Magazine |publisher=St Ann's Parish Church |date=Christmas 2007 |title=The Comer Brothers}}</ref>\n\nMusicians who have lived in the area include [[Morrissey]], the front man of 1980s alternative rock band [[the Smiths]], whose family moved to King's Road in Stretford when he was 10 years old. [[Ian Curtis]], the lead singer of [[Joy Division]], was born in Stretford. [[Jay Kay]], lead singer and songwriter of [[Jamiroquai]], was born in Stretford in 1969. Oscar-nominated film maker [[Mark Gill]] was raised in Stretford, where in 2016 he made a film about Morrissey's early life.<ref name=\"mail\">{{citation |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3579794/War-Peace-star-Jack-Lowden-transforms-young-Morrisey-films-new-biopic-Steven.html |title=This Charming Man! War & Peace star Jack Lowden transforms into a young Morrissey as he films new biopic Steven |work=MailOnline |date=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nA number of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] players, including some of those who died in the [[Munich air disaster]] of February 1958, lived in lodgings at 19 Gorse Avenue. A blue plaque was unveiled at the house by former lodger and Munich survivor [[Bobby Charlton|Sir Bobby Charlton]] in recognition of the house's association with Manchester United. The owner of the house during the 1950s was Margaret Watson, but by the time of the plaque's unveiling more than 50 years later it was occupied by a different family.<ref>{{citation |last=Devine |first=Peter |title=Video: Busby Babes Duncan Edwards and Tommy Taylor honoured with plaques on the walls of their Stretford 'digs' |date=8 July 2011 |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1426236_video-busby-babes-duncan-edwards-and-tommy-taylor-honoured-with-plaques-on-the-walls-of-their-stretford-digs |work=Manchester Evening News |access-date=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Stretford]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist|notes=}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"2014LocalElection\">\n{{cite web |title=Clifford |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council |url=http://www.infotrafford.org.uk/profiles/profile?profileId=564&geoTypeId=33&geoIds=00BUGE#ctl00_mainContentPlaceHolder_profileReport_564 |access-date=2 June 2014 |mode=cs2}}<br /> \u2022 {{cite web |title=Gorse Hill |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council |url=http://www.infotrafford.org.uk/profiles/profile?profileId=564&geoTypeId=33&geoIds=00BUGJ |access-date=2 June 2014 |mode=cs2}}<br /> \u2022 {{cite web |title=Longford |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council |url=http://www.infotrafford.org.uk/profiles/profile?profileId=564&geoTypeId=33&geoIds=00BUGM |access-date=2 June 2014 |mode=cs2}}<br /> \u2022 {{cite web |title=Stretford |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council |url=http://www.infotrafford.org.uk/profiles/profile?profileId=564&geoTypeId=33&geoIds=00BUGR |access-date=2 June 2014 |mode=cs2}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Climate01\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/uk.html |title=Annual UK weather averages |publisher=Met Office |access-date=23 April 2007 |mode=cs2 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705140124/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/uk.html |archivedate=5 July 2009 |df=dmy}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Constitution\">\n{{citation |title=Trafford Council Constitution Part 2 |publisher=Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council |url=http://www.trafford.gov.uk/about-your-council/about-us/docs/part-2-constitution-articles.pdf |access-date=2 June 2014}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"EconomicSex\">\n{{cite web |title=KS601EW to KS603EW \u2013 Economic activity by sex |url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/select/getdatasetbytheme.asp?opt=3&theme=&subgrp= |work=nomis |publisher=Office for National Statistics |access-date=27 November 2017}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Employment\">\n{{cite web |title=KS605UK \u2013 Industry |url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/select/getdatasetbytheme.asp?opt=3&theme=&subgrp= |work=nomis |publisher=Office for National Statistics |access-date=27 November 2017}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gazetteer\">\n{{citation|title=Greater Manchester Gazetteer |publisher=Greater Manchester County Record Office |url=http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazzs.htm |access-date=2 July 2007 |at=Places names&nbsp;\u2013 S |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718144349/http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazzs.htm |archivedate=18 July 2011 }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Income\">\n{{cite web |title=Clifford (Ward), Income: Model-Based Estimates |publisher=Office for National Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=5941521&c=clifford&d=14&e=4&g=356197&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1197468329384&enc=1&dsFamilyId=266 |access-date=12 December 2007 |mode=cs2}}<br /> \u2022 {{cite web |title=Longford (Ward), Income: Model-Based Estimates |publisher=Office for National Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=5941516&c=longford&d=14&e=4&g=356356&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1197467359802&enc=1&dsFamilyId=266 |access-date=12 December 2007 |mode=