perated by J. Marvin Herndon\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herndon, J. Marvin}}\n[[Category:American nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:Astrophysics]]\n[[Category:American geophysicists]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M University alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTheories on Earth:This is a minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._Marvin_Herndon"}
{"title_page": "Pratiksha Apurv", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian painter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = File:Pratiksha1.jpg\n| name               = Pratishka Apurv\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = [[Gadarwara|Madhya Pradesh, India]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| occupation         = Dress Designer, Painter\n}}\n'''Pratiksha Apurv''' is an Indian painter. Her work is based on her uncle [[Osho (Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh)|Osho]]'s teachings. Before moving to painting, Apurv was a successful fashion designer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tankha|first= Madhur|title= Reflecting the Journey in Solitude|url= http://thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/article924739.ece|accessdate=7 December 2013|newspaper=The Hindu|date=1 December 2010}}</ref> Apurv won the National Award 2015-16<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.htsyndication.com/htsportal/article/Lalit-Kala-Akademi-to-honour-Osho-s-niece-for-her-artwork/11828856|title=Lalit Kala Akademi to honour Osho's niece for her artwork|date=7 March 2016|newspaper=Hindustan Times|access-date=|url-status=dead}}</ref> given by the [[Lalit Kala Akademi|Lalit Kala Akademi,]] Ministry of Culture for her painting titled 'Cosmic Balance', and has exhibited her paintings across the country. Her 'Mystical Moments' series of paintings at the Rashtrapati Bhawan Museum was attended by President [[Pranab Mukherjee]], Vice President [[Hamid Ansari]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] on July 25, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Latha|first=CSS|title=Canvas Queen|url=http://www.savvy.co.in/article/features/canvas-queen/11771|newspaper=Savvy |date=10 October 2016}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nPratiksha Apurv was born in [[Gadarwara|Madhya Pradesh, India]], the niece of [[Rajneesh|Osho]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Malkarnekar|first= Gauri|title= Osho's niece takes his teachings to international level|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-11-17/goa/44161263_1_osho-pratiksha-apurv-teachings|accessdate=1 December 2013|newspaper=Times of India |date=17 November 2013}}</ref> Her father Vijay Bharti is his younger brother. She took ''[[Sannyasa|sannyas]]'' at the age of 11 and attended the Osho ''[[ashram]]'' in [[Poona|Pune]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|first=|url=http://indianexpress.com/news/spirited-expressions/1098710/|title=Spirited Expressions|date=7 April 2013|newspaper=Indian Express|access-date=20 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1982, she moved to [[Rajneeshpuram]] in the United States and stayed with her uncle.\n\n==Professional life==\n\nIn 1987 Apurv launched the Oshonik label of apparel, eventually designing for Atal Bihari Vajpayee, [[Vinod Khanna]], [[Amjad Ali Khan]], Hansraj Hans, Kapil dev, [[Zakir Hussain (musician)|Zakir Hussain]] and others.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dhiman|first= Munish|title=Spiritual motifs|url= http://sunday-guardian.com/young-restless/spiritual-motifs-and-forms-make-for-visions-of-the-divine|newspaper=Sunday Guardian |date=13 April 2013}}</ref>  She also writes a regular column in ''The Speaking Tree'', a spiritual publication of ''[[The Times of India]]''.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/books/book-launches/a-collection-of-deeply-spiritual-pieces-by-pratiksha-apurv-launched/articleshow/65706811.cms|title=A collection of deeply spiritual pieces by Pratiksha Apurv launched - Times of India|last=|first=|date=6 September 2018|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2003 she retired from dress design and began to paint.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Meditative art==\n\nHer paintings are full of religious imagery, [[spirtuality|spiritual]] icons, and [[abstraction|abstract]] symbols. She describes her work as an ongoing rendering of her spiritual journey. Apurv has also contemporary figures silhouetted in black against a colourful background featuring people engaged in various forms of social interaction like dancing with one another or engrossed in quiet, intimate dialogue. Some of her paintings have strong overtones of [[Tibetan art|Tibetan]] influences such as \"Jalpari,\" which has a colourful mythological figure rising out of the water against an elaborately detailed sky.<ref>{{cite news|last=Narayanan|first= Sharadha|title=Expressing spirituality through art|url= http://newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article26561.ece?service=print|newspaper=New Indian Express|date=7 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Paitande|first= Priyadarshini|title=Art as Meditation|url=http://hindu.com/mp/2009/01/07/stories/2009010750320500.htm|newspaper=The Hindu|date=7 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nA Muslim figure praying behind a finely detailed fretwork screen in the painting titled 'Devotion' and a tranquil [[Buddha]] head with rays of light radiating around it in the one titled 'Illuminations'.\n\nShe considers moments in [[meditation]] and deep experience of silence can be felt expressed through the depth of colours and a close-knit relationship between creator and structure.<ref>{{cite news|author=Times of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-04-06/vadodara/28114091_1_canvas-osho-artists|title=Pearls of meditation on canvas|date=6 April 2010|newspaper=Times of India}}</ref>\n\nHer first solo show was attended by former Prime Minister [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn her Second series of Spiritual Odyssey exhibition at [[National Centre for the Performing Arts (India)|NCPA]] Mumbai, Apurv painted the Osho's wisdom on canvas, which were praised by critics.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last=Dhingra|first= Deepali|title=OSHO's teachings, in a brush stroke|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2007-09-27/mumbai/27975004_1_painting-exhibition-osho-pratiksha-apurv|newspaper=Times of India|date=27 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn one of her exhibitions at lalit Kala Academy, New Delhi, Apurv launched her [[Upanishad]] Collection. Former national Security advisor [[Brajesh Mishra]] inaugurated the show.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tankha|first= Madhur|title=Spiritual experience spills over on canvas|url= http://thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/spiritual-experience-spills-over-on-canvas/article1236802.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=11 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, her exhibition at L&P Hutheesing Visual art centre, was attended by Gujarat Chief Minister [[Narendra Modi|Narendra Modi.]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Dhadake|first= Ramesh|title=Narendra Modi visits Painting exhibition|url= http://deshgujarat.com/2010/03/26/narendra-modi-visits-painting-exhibitionphotos/|newspaper=Desh Gujarat|date=26 March 2010}}</ref> \n\nHer latest series is 'Mystical Moments'.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHer book ''The Mystic and Her Colours'' was launched by film maker [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] and [[Rekha Bhardwaj]] on 5 September 2018 in Mumbai.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Achievements==\n\nApurv's paintings were selected for the 'Soul of Asia' section of the 44th International Film Festival of India [[IFFI]] held in November 2013 in Goa.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|last=Express|first= Indian|title= Mystic Moments|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/mystic-moments/1197024|newspaper=Indian Express|date=Nov 2013}}</ref> The show <ref>{{cite news|last=Latha|first=CSS|url=http://www.magnamags.com/society/Reinterpreting-Osho%E2%80%98isms%E2%80%99/10024|title=Reinterpreting Osho'isms'|date=Dec 2015|newspaper=Society|access-date=|url-status=dead}}</ref> was inaugurated by  [[Manish Tewari]] and [[Susan Sarandon]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bureau|first= Press Information|title=Manish Tewari Inaugurates Art Exhibition 'Soul in Art\" at 44th IFFI |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/mbErel.aspx?relid=100775|newspaper=PIB, Govt of India|date=21 Nov 2013}}</ref> The festival also screened the film ''Master of the Masters'' featuring 22 of her paintings.\n\nShe won the National Award 2015-16 for her painting titled 'Cosmic Balance'.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last=Sinha|first= Arunav|title= Atal's ex-dress designer lands in Lucknow to display her artistic acumen|url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Atals-ex-dress-designer-lands-in-Lucknow-to-display-her-artistic-acumen/articleshow/51317926.cms|newspaper=Times Of India|date=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lalitkala.gov.in/upload/57NEA/List%20of%20National%20Awardees-57NEA.pdf|title=57th National Exhibition of Art 2015 - 2016|last=|first=|date=2016|website=Lalit Kala Akademi New Delhi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>Her work was also part of National Exhibition in Lucknow on March 10, 2016 that was inaugurated by Ram Naik, Governor of Uttar Pradesh.  Her paintings were selected for India's national exhibition organised by [[Lalit Kala Akademi]], New Delhi for the 52nd, 53rd and 54th National Exhibition.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mehta|first= Kamini|title=Osho's teachings find a canvas|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-09/chandigarh/38402693_1_osho-painting-exhibition-lalit-kala-akademi|newspaper=Times of India|date=9 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nApurv's painting titled 'Whirling' was used for the cover page of the book ''Introducing new age Islam,''  released during the UN Human rights meeting in Geneva this year.\n\nIndian Council for Cultural Relations (ICCR) magazine \"Indian Horizons\" has featured Images of 34 paintings for their special issue (Oct\u2013Dec, 2011) published in March 2012The paintings are used as illustrations in the magazine for \"Vedanta & Spirituality\".\n\nSome of her paintings appeared in [[Vikram Chopra|Vikram Chopra's]] book ''Shakespeare: The Indian Icon'' published in 2011. She was also a member of a jury for  'Swedish Innovations - Indian Interpretations' photo contest that was organised by Embassy of Sweden in 2012 at New Delhi.\n\n==Exhibition==\n\n1. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" AIFACS Gallery New Delhi, Feb 2007.\n\n2. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" NCPA Gallery Mumbai, Sep 2007.\n\n3. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" Lalit Kala Akademi,March 2008.\n\n4. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" Chitrakala Parishath, Bangalore,Dec 2008.\n\n5. Solo Show -\"Spiritual Odyssey\" Lalit Kala Akademi, Chennai, Jan 2009.\n\n6. Solo show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" L&P Hutheesing Visual art centre, Ahmedabad, March 2010.\n\n7. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" Allure Art gallery, Vadodara, April 2010.\n\n8. Solo Show- \"Reflections\" Lalit Kala Akademi,New Delhi,Nov\u2013Dec 2010.\n\n9. Solo Show- \"Reflections\" ICCR, New Delhi,July 2011.\n\n10. Solo Show-\"Selected works of Pratiksha\" Punjab Kala Bhawan, Chandigarh, April 2013.\n\n11. Solo show- \"Divine Art\" INOX, IFFI Goa, November 2013\n\n12. Solo Show- \"Mystical Moments\" Rashtrapati Bhawan Museum, New Delhi, July 2016\n\n13. Solo Show- \"Mystical Moments\" Lalit Kala Akademi, New Delhi, March 2018\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Rajneesh movement]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pratikshaart.com/index.php Pratiksha Apurv Profile]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apurv, Pratiksha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian painters]]\n[[Category:Indian women painters]]\n[[Category:Rajneesh movement]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women artists]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Painters from Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian painter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = File:Pratiksha1.jpg\n| name               = Pratishka Apurv\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = [[Gadarwara|Madhya Pradesh, India]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| occupation         = Dress Designer, Painter\n}}\n'''Pratiksha Apurv''' is an Indian painter. Her work is based on her uncle [[Osho (Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh)|Osho]]'s teachings. Before moving to painting, Apurv was a successful fashion designer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tankha|first= Madhur|title= Reflecting the Journey in Solitude|url= http://thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/article924739.ece|accessdate=7 December 2013|newspaper=The Hindu|date=1 December 2010}}</ref> Apurv won the National Award 2015-16<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.htsyndication.com/htsportal/article/Lalit-Kala-Akademi-to-honour-Osho-s-niece-for-her-artwork/11828856|title=Lalit Kala Akademi to honour Osho's niece for her artwork|date=7 March 2016|newspaper=Hindustan Times|access-date=|url-status=dead}}</ref> given by the [[Lalit Kala Akademi|Lalit Kala Akademi,]] Ministry of Culture for her painting titled 'Cosmic Balance', and has exhibited her paintings across the country. Her 'Mystical Moments' series of paintings at the Rashtrapati Bhawan Museum was attended by President [[Pranab Mukherjee]], Vice President [[Hamid Ansari]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] on July 25, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Latha|first=CSS|title=Canvas Queen|url=http://www.savvy.co.in/article/features/canvas-queen/11771|newspaper=Savvy |date=10 October 2016}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nPratiksha Apurv was born in [[Gadarwara|Madhya Pradesh, India]], the the niece of [[Rajneesh|Osho]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Malkarnekar|first= Gauri|title= Osho's niece takes his teachings to international level|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-11-17/goa/44161263_1_osho-pratiksha-apurv-teachings|accessdate=1 December 2013|newspaper=Times of India |date=17 November 2013}}</ref> Her father Vijay Bharti is his younger brother. She took ''[[Sannyasa|sannyas]]'' at the age of 11 and attended the Osho ''[[ashram]]'' in [[Poona|Pune]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|first=|url=http://indianexpress.com/news/spirited-expressions/1098710/|title=Spirited Expressions|date=7 April 2013|newspaper=Indian Express|access-date=20 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1982, she moved to [[Rajneeshpuram]] in the United States and stayed with her uncle.\n\n==Professional life==\n\nIn 1987 Apurv launched the Oshonik label of apparel, eventually designing for Atal Bihari Vajpayee, [[Vinod Khanna]], [[Amjad Ali Khan]], Hansraj Hans, Kapil dev, [[Zakir Hussain (musician)|Zakir Hussain]] and others.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dhiman|first= Munish|title=Spiritual motifs|url= http://sunday-guardian.com/young-restless/spiritual-motifs-and-forms-make-for-visions-of-the-divine|newspaper=Sunday Guardian |date=13 April 2013}}</ref>  She also writes a regular column in ''The Speaking Tree'', a spiritual publication of ''[[The Times of India]]''.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/books/book-launches/a-collection-of-deeply-spiritual-pieces-by-pratiksha-apurv-launched/articleshow/65706811.cms|title=A collection of deeply spiritual pieces by Pratiksha Apurv launched - Times of India|last=|first=|date=6 September 2018|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2003 she retired from dress design and began to paint.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Meditative art==\n\nHer paintings are full of religious imagery, [[spirtuality|spiritual]] icons, and [[abstraction|abstract]] symbols. She describes her work as an ongoing rendering of her spiritual journey. Apurv has also contemporary figures silhouetted in black against a colourful background featuring people engaged in various forms of social interaction like dancing with one another or engrossed in quiet, intimate dialogue. Some of her paintings have strong overtones of [[Tibetan art|Tibetan]] influences such as \"Jalpari,\" which has a colourful mythological figure rising out of the water against an elaborately detailed sky.<ref>{{cite news|last=Narayanan|first= Sharadha|title=Expressing spirituality through art|url= http://newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article26561.ece?service=print|newspaper=New Indian Express|date=7 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Paitande|first= Priyadarshini|title=Art as Meditation|url=http://hindu.com/mp/2009/01/07/stories/2009010750320500.htm|newspaper=The Hindu|date=7 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nA Muslim figure praying behind a finely detailed fretwork screen in the painting titled 'Devotion' and a tranquil [[Buddha]] head with rays of light radiating around it in the one titled 'Illuminations'.\n\nShe considers moments in [[meditation]] and deep experience of silence can be felt expressed through the depth of colours and a close-knit relationship between creator and structure.<ref>{{cite news|author=Times of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-04-06/vadodara/28114091_1_canvas-osho-artists|title=Pearls of meditation on canvas|date=6 April 2010|newspaper=Times of India}}</ref>\n\nHer first solo show was attended by former Prime Minister [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn her Second series of Spiritual Odyssey exhibition at [[National Centre for the Performing Arts (India)|NCPA]] Mumbai, Apurv painted the Osho's wisdom on canvas, which were praised by critics.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last=Dhingra|first= Deepali|title=OSHO's teachings, in a brush stroke|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2007-09-27/mumbai/27975004_1_painting-exhibition-osho-pratiksha-apurv|newspaper=Times of India|date=27 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn one of her exhibitions at lalit Kala Academy, New Delhi, Apurv launched her [[Upanishad]] Collection. Former national Security advisor [[Brajesh Mishra]] inaugurated the show.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tankha|first= Madhur|title=Spiritual experience spills over on canvas|url= http://thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/spiritual-experience-spills-over-on-canvas/article1236802.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=11 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, her exhibition at L&P Hutheesing Visual art centre, was attended by Gujarat Chief Minister [[Narendra Modi|Narendra Modi.]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Dhadake|first= Ramesh|title=Narendra Modi visits Painting exhibition|url= http://deshgujarat.com/2010/03/26/narendra-modi-visits-painting-exhibitionphotos/|newspaper=Desh Gujarat|date=26 March 2010}}</ref> \n\nHer latest series is 'Mystical Moments'.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHer book ''The Mystic and Her Colours'' was launched by film maker [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] and [[Rekha Bhardwaj]] on 5 September 2018 in Mumbai.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Achievements==\n\nApurv's paintings were selected for the 'Soul of Asia' section of the 44th International Film Festival of India [[IFFI]] held in November 2013 in Goa.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|last=Express|first= Indian|title= Mystic Moments|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/mystic-moments/1197024|newspaper=Indian Express|date=Nov 2013}}</ref> The show <ref>{{cite news|last=Latha|first=CSS|url=http://www.magnamags.com/society/Reinterpreting-Osho%E2%80%98isms%E2%80%99/10024|title=Reinterpreting Osho'isms'|date=Dec 2015|newspaper=Society|access-date=|url-status=dead}}</ref> was inaugurated by  [[Manish Tewari]] and [[Susan Sarandon]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bureau|first= Press Information|title=Manish Tewari Inaugurates Art Exhibition 'Soul in Art\" at 44th IFFI |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/mbErel.aspx?relid=100775|newspaper=PIB, Govt of India|date=21 Nov 2013}}</ref> The festival also screened the film ''Master of the Masters'' featuring 22 of her paintings.\n\nShe won the National Award 2015-16 for her painting titled 'Cosmic Balance'.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last=Sinha|first= Arunav|title= Atal's ex-dress designer lands in Lucknow to display her artistic acumen|url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Atals-ex-dress-designer-lands-in-Lucknow-to-display-her-artistic-acumen/articleshow/51317926.cms|newspaper=Times Of India|date=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lalitkala.gov.in/upload/57NEA/List%20of%20National%20Awardees-57NEA.pdf|title=57th National Exhibition of Art 2015 - 2016|last=|first=|date=2016|website=Lalit Kala Akademi New Delhi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>Her work was also part of National Exhibition in Lucknow on March 10, 2016 that was inaugurated by Ram Naik, Governor of Uttar Pradesh.  Her paintings were selected for India's national exhibition organised by [[Lalit Kala Akademi]], New Delhi for the 52nd, 53rd and 54th National Exhibition.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mehta|first= Kamini|title=Osho's teachings find a canvas|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-09/chandigarh/38402693_1_osho-painting-exhibition-lalit-kala-akademi|newspaper=Times of India|date=9 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nApurv's painting titled 'Whirling' was used for the cover page of the book ''Introducing new age Islam,''  released during the UN Human rights meeting in Geneva this year.\n\nIndian Council for Cultural Relations (ICCR) magazine \"Indian Horizons\" has featured Images of 34 paintings for their special issue (Oct\u2013Dec, 2011) published in March 2012The paintings are used as illustrations in the magazine for \"Vedanta & Spirituality\".\n\nSome of her paintings appeared in [[Vikram Chopra|Vikram Chopra's]] book ''Shakespeare: The Indian Icon'' published in 2011. She was also a member of a jury for  'Swedish Innovations - Indian Interpretations' photo contest that was organised by Embassy of Sweden in 2012 at New Delhi.\n\n==Exhibition==\n\n1. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" AIFACS Gallery New Delhi, Feb 2007.\n\n2. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" NCPA Gallery Mumbai, Sep 2007.\n\n3. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" Lalit Kala Akademi,March 2008.\n\n4. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" Chitrakala Parishath, Bangalore,Dec 2008.\n\n5. Solo Show -\"Spiritual Odyssey\" Lalit Kala Akademi, Chennai, Jan 2009.\n\n6. Solo show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" L&P Hutheesing Visual art centre, Ahmedabad, March 2010.\n\n7. Solo Show- \"Spiritual Odyssey\" Allure Art gallery, Vadodara, April 2010.\n\n8. Solo Show- \"Reflections\" Lalit Kala Akademi,New Delhi,Nov\u2013Dec 2010.\n\n9. Solo Show- \"Reflections\" ICCR, New Delhi,July 2011.\n\n10. Solo Show-\"Selected works of Pratiksha\" Punjab Kala Bhawan, Chandigarh, April 2013.\n\n11. Solo show- \"Divine Art\" INOX, IFFI Goa, November 2013\n\n12. Solo Show- \"Mystical Moments\" Rashtrapati Bhawan Museum, New Delhi, July 2016\n\n13. Solo Show- \"Mystical Moments\" Lalit Kala Akademi, New Delhi, March 2018\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Rajneesh movement]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pratikshaart.com/index.php Pratiksha Apurv Profile]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Apurv, Pratiksha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian painters]]\n[[Category:Indian women painters]]\n[[Category:Rajneesh movement]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women artists]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Painters from Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:21st-century women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pratiksha_Apurv"}
{"title_page": "Gugging", "text_new": "{{short description|Psychiatric institution near Vienna, Austria}}\n[[File:Haus der K\u00fcnstler vom Osten.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|The building in 2010]]\nThe '''Maria Gugging Psychiatric Clinic''', known as '''Gugging''', is a [[psychiatric institution]] located on the outskirts of [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].<ref>http://www.gugging.at/en/besucherinfo/kontakt-anreise</ref> Several of its patients became known for their [[Outsider Art]], and were referred to as the '''Gugging Artists'''. Today, the artist/patients live in a dedicated [[art therapy]] center at Gugging, known as the Art / Brut Center Gugging. In stark contrast, Gugging has a darkened history during the time of the Nazi Regime, when hundreds of mental patients were murdered or abused as part of the [[Aktion T4|Nazi Regime Euthanasia Program]].\n\n==History during the Nazi regime==\nHistorian Herwig Czech told the Austrian Press Agency that Gugging was the scene \u201cof some of the most barbarous medical crimes committed in Austria\u201d during the Nazi Regime.  Approximately 400 patients were killed by Doctor Emil Gelny by poisoning and electric shock.  Rudolf Lonauer was the attending doctor for 112 deaths and typically murdered his patients - mainly women - with an overdose of drugs. Patients also died from lethal injection, malnutrition, and infectious diseases.  New research has also shown that between November 1940 and May 1941 a total of 675 people were taken from the clinic to the euthanasia center at [[Hartheim Euthanasia Centre|Hartheim]] castle near [[Linz]], where they were gassed.  Of these, 116 were children and teenagers between the ages of four and 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nazis killed hundreds at Austrian mental hospital|url=http://www.thelocal.at/20141125/nazis-killed-hundreds-at-austrian-mental-hospital|website=The Local|publisher=The Local|accessdate=14 February 2017}}</ref>  \n\nBy 1940, rumors of euthanasia at Hartheim began to spread.  Anna W\u00f6dl, a nurse and the mother of a disabled child living at Gugging, attempted to save the life of her son by petitioning against his relocation to Hartheim.  She was assured that he would not go to Hartheim, but was instead taken to another children's institution, [[Am Spiegelgrund]], where he died soon after he arrived.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alfred W\u00f6dl|url=http://www.t4-denkmal.de/eng/Alfred-Woedl|website=The Memorial Page of Victims of Nazi Euthanasia Programs|publisher=Germany National Memorial|accessdate=14 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==The Gugging Artists==\nIn the late 1950s, [[psychiatrist]] [[Leo Navratil]] (1921-2006), of the Maria Gugging Psychiatric Clinic, had his patients produce drawings for diagnostic purposes. The following year he discovered artistically talented individuals in his ward - a finding that was confirmed by [[Jean Dubuffet]], the French artist who coined the term Art Brut (also known as [[Outsider Art]]). Navratil's first book ''Schizophrenie und Kunst'' (''Schizophrenia and Art'') was published in 1965. Attracted to the clinic by this work, many Viennese artists visited Gugging. In 1970 the first exhibition of the \"Gugging Artists\" took place in a Vienna gallery. Thereafter, the \"Gugging Artists\" were frequently presented in galleries and museums.\n\n==House of Artists==\n[[File:Vojo al muzeo.JPG|thumb|Tiled art in the clinic grounds]]\nThe \"Center for Art and Psychotherapy\" was founded by Navratil in 1981. He invited artistically talented patients to live in the house, which serves as living space, studio, gallery and meeting place. With the founder's retirement in 1986, Johann Feilacher became his successor. Feilacher stressed the role that art played at Gugging and went on to change its name to the \"House of Artists\" ({{lang-de|Haus der K\u00fcnstler}}). Within Europe, the House of Artists is regarded as a model for psychiatric reforms based on [[art therapy]] as a means to reintegrate clients into society.\n\nPresently, a [[cultural center]] is located next to the House of Artists. It is known as the \"Art / Brut Center\", and consists of a museum, a gallery and a public studio. The museum contains the works of the Gugging artists, and also hosts traveling Art Brut exhibitions, which include artists such as [[Martin Ramirez]] and [[Adolf W\u00f6lfli]]. The museum building also hosts a public studio that is open to all, but is mainly used by individuals who have undergone or are receiving psychiatric treatment. Together the museum, the gallery, the \"House of Artists\" and the public studio, are known as the Art / Brut Center Gugging. \n\n==In popular culture== \nIn early 1994 [[David Bowie]] and [[Brian Eno]] visited the Gugging psychiatric hospital to interview and photograph the celebrated artist-patients famous for their \"Outsider Art\". <ref name=nytb>{{citation | url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/moody-bowie.html | title=Returning to the Sound of Those Golden Years | first=Rick | last=Moody | date=10 September 1995 | accessdate=29 October 2013 | journal=[[New York Times]]}}</ref> Artistic materials favored by the Gugging's residents had a powerful influence on production strategies in the studio <ref name=nytb /> during the Bowie / Eno collaboration. In March 1994 a three-hour piece (mostly dialog) further inspired the process of the 1995 concept album ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]]''.\n\n[[Philipp Weiss]]'s ''[[Ein sch\u00f6ner Hase ist meistens der Einzellne]]'' is based on the real life story of Ernst Herbeck (1920 - 1991) and August Walla (1936 - 2001), two schizophrenic artistic patients of Gugging. [[Projekttheater Vorarlberg]] performed a production of the play at [[Alte Hallenbad Feldkirch]] from December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vol.at/projekttheater-vorarlberg-nimmt-schizophrene-kuenstler-in-den-fokus/3799037|title=Projekttheater Vorarlberg nimmt schizophrene K\u00fcnstler in den Fokus|publisher=Vol.at|accessdate=20 April 2020|language=German}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.gugging.org/ Art/Brut Center Gugging website]\n*[https://vimeo.com/28318418/ Short Film on Gugging by The Museum of Everything // www.musevery.com]\n\n{{coords|48.313|16.258|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Psychotherapy]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in Austria]]\n[[Category:Outsider art]]\n[[Category:Art therapy]]\n[[Category:Museums in Lower Austria]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Psychiatric institution near Vienna, Austria}}\n[[File:Haus der K\u00fcnstler vom Osten.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|The building in 2010]]\nThe '''Maria Gugging Psychiatric Clinic''', known as '''Gugging''', is a [[psychiatric institution]] located on the outskirts of [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].<ref>http://www.gugging.at/en/besucherinfo/kontakt-anreise</ref> Several of its patients became known for their [[Outsider Art]], and were referred to as the '''Gugging Artists'''. Today, the artist/patients live in a dedicated [[art therapy]] center at Gugging, known as the Art / Brut Center Gugging. In stark contrast, Gugging has a darkened history during the time of the Nazi Regime, when hundreds of mental patients were murdered or abused as part of the [[Aktion T4|Nazi Regime Euthanasia Program]].\n\n==History during the Nazi regime==\nHistorian Herwig Czech told the Austrian Press Agency that Gugging was the scene \u201cof some of the most barbarous medical crimes committed in Austria\u201d during the Nazi Regime.  Approximately 400 patients were killed by Doctor Emil Gelny by poisoning and electric shock.  Rudolf Lonauer was the attending doctor for 112 deaths and typically murdered his patients - mainly women - with an overdose of drugs. Patients also died from lethal injection, malnutrition, and infectious diseases.  New research has also shown that between November 1940 and May 1941 a total of 675 people were taken from the clinic to the euthanasia center at [[Hartheim Euthanasia Centre|Hartheim]] castle near [[Linz]], where they were gassed.  Of these, 116 were children and teenagers between the ages of four and 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nazis killed hundreds at Austrian mental hospital|url=http://www.thelocal.at/20141125/nazis-killed-hundreds-at-austrian-mental-hospital|website=The Local|publisher=The Local|accessdate=14 February 2017}}</ref>  \n\nBy 1940, rumors of euthanasia at Hartheim began to spread.  Anna W\u00f6dl, a nurse and the mother of a disabled child living at Gugging, attempted to save the life of her son by petitioning against his relocation to Hartheim.  She was assured that he would not go to Hartheim, but was instead taken to another children's institution, [[Am Spiegelgrund]], where he died soon after he arrived.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alfred W\u00f6dl|url=http://www.t4-denkmal.de/eng/Alfred-Woedl|website=The Memorial Page of Victims of Nazi Euthanasia Programs|publisher=Germany National Memorial|accessdate=14 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==The Gugging Artists==\nIn the late 1950s, [[psychiatrist]] [[Leo Navratil]] (1921-2006), of the Maria Gugging Psychiatric Clinic, had his patients produce drawings for diagnostic purposes. The following year he discovered artistically talented individuals in his ward - a finding that was confirmed by [[Jean Dubuffet]], the French artist who coined the term Art Brut (also known as [[Outsider Art]]). Navratil's first book ''Schizophrenie und Kunst'' (''Schizophrenia and Art'') was published in 1965. Attracted to the clinic by this work, many Viennese artists visited Gugging. In 1970 the first exhibition of the \"Gugging Artists\" took place in a Vienna gallery. Thereafter, the \"Gugging Artists\" were frequently presented in galleries and museums.\n\n==House of Artists==\n[[File:Vojo al muzeo.JPG|thumb|Tiled art in the clinic grounds]]\nThe \"Center for Art and Psychotherapy\" was founded by Navratil in 1981. He invited artistically talented patients to live in the house, which serves as living space, studio, gallery and meeting place. With the founder's retirement in 1986, Johann Feilacher became his successor. Feilacher stressed the role that art played at Gugging and went on to change its name to the \"House of Artists\" ({{lang-de|Haus der K\u00fcnstler}}). Within Europe, the House of Artists is regarded as a model for psychiatric reforms based on [[art therapy]] as a means to reintegrate clients into society.\n\nPresently, a [[cultural center]] is located next to the House of Artists. It is known as the \"Art / Brut Center\", and consists of a museum, a gallery and a public studio. The museum contains the works of the Gugging artists, and also hosts traveling Art Brut exhibitions, which include artists such as [[Martin Ramirez]] and [[Adolf W\u00f6lfli]]. The museum building also hosts a public studio that is open to all, but is mainly used by individuals who have undergone or are receiving psychiatric treatment. Together the museum, the gallery, the \"House of Artists\" and the public studio, are known as the Art / Brut Center Gugging. \n\n==In popular culture== \nIn early 1994 [[David Bowie]] and [[Brian Eno]] visited the Gugging psychiatric hospital to interview and photograph the celebrated artist-patients famous for their \"Outsider Art\". <ref name=nytb>{{citation | url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/reviews/moody-bowie.html | title=Returning to the Sound of Those Golden Years | first=Rick | last=Moody | date=10 September 1995 | accessdate=29 October 2013 | journal=[[New York Times]]}}</ref> Artistic materials favored by the Gugging's residents had a powerful influence on production strategies in the studio <ref name=nytb /> during the Bowie / Eno collaboration. In March 1994 a three-hour piece (mostly dialog) further inspired the process of the 1995 concept album ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]]''.\n\n[[Philipp Weiss]]'s ''[[Ein sch\u00f6ner Hase ist meistens der Einzellne]]'' is based on the the real life story of Ernst Herbeck (1920 - 1991) and August Walla (1936 - 2001), two schizophrenic artistic patients of Gugging. [[Projekttheater Vorarlberg]] performed a production of the play at [[Alte Hallenbad Feldkirch]] from December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vol.at/projekttheater-vorarlberg-nimmt-schizophrene-kuenstler-in-den-fokus/3799037|title=Projekttheater Vorarlberg nimmt schizophrene K\u00fcnstler in den Fokus|publisher=Vol.at|accessdate=20 April 2020|language=German}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.gugging.org/ Art/Brut Center Gugging website]\n*[https://vimeo.com/28318418/ Short Film on Gugging by The Museum of Everything // www.musevery.com]\n\n{{coords|48.313|16.258|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Psychotherapy]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in Austria]]\n[[Category:Outsider art]]\n[[Category:Art therapy]]\n[[Category:Museums in Lower Austria]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Austria]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gugging"}
{"title_page": "Bais Chana Women International", "text_new": "{{short description|Chabad school}}\n'''Bais Chana Women International''' is a [[Chabad]] non-profit organization that works to provide an environment for Jewish girls and women, ages 15 and up and from all backgrounds, to explore Jewish teachings and traditions.<ref>Great Nonprofits, 2010, [http://greatnonprofits.org/reviews/profile2/bais-chana-women-international-inc]\", May 26, 2010</ref><ref>Bais Chana International, 2009, [http://www.baischana.org/content/view/135/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723073011/http://www.baischana.org/content/view/135/ |date=2011-07-23 }}\". June 8, 2010</ref>\n\nBais Chana\u2019s founding was inspired and motivated by  the [[Chabad|Lubavitcher]] Rebbe, Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]]'s support of Jewish education for all women.<ref name=\"bc.org\">Bais Chana International, 2005-2010, {{cite web|url=http://www.baischana.org/content/view/13/124/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504094248/http://www.baischana.org/content/view/13/124/ |archivedate=2010-05-04 }}\", May 26, 2010.</ref> In 1971, its first home was opened in the Twin Cities, Minnesota.<ref name=\"bc.org\" /> In 1991 the organization began diversifying its program to include shorter retreat segments in locations around the world.<ref name=\"bc.org\" /> \nWomen of all ages and little or no formal background in Jewish traditions have taken part in these educational retreats, which include classes, group study, private tutoring and mentoring.<ref name=\"bc.org\"/> \n\nThe full class schedule explores life as a Jewish woman through hands-on projects such as [[challah]] baking, along with discussions and in-depth study of [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] texts, [[Torah]], prayer, Bible commentary, [[Midrash]], [[Maimonides]], [[Kabbalah]], [[Talmud]] and more. The rotating teaching staff features Bais Chana's co-founder, Rabbi [[Manis Friedman]].<ref name=\"bc.org\" /><ref name=\"bc.org\" /><ref>Philadelphia Jewish Exponent Staff. \"Women Study: A traveling educational program engages women in a deeper perspective of their Jewish tradition\". Rpt on Chabad.org on Mar 5 1999. Chabad-Lubavitch  Media Center. 2001-2010 [http://www.chabad.org/news/article_cdo/aid/409/jewish/Women-Study.htm%20%28this%20originally%20appeared%20in%20a%20Philly%20paper]\"</ref>\n<ref>Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center. 2001-2010. [http://www.chabad.org/search/keyword_cdo/kid/469/jewish/Friedman-Manis.htm]\"</ref> \n\nUnder the direction of Mrs. Hinda Leah Sharfstein, Bais Chana is now headquartered in New York and has further expanded to include three annual sessions at an array of venues across the United States, including learning retreats for couples, the Snorkel and Study Program, and The Jewish Un-Camp.<ref name=\"bc.org\" /><ref>Olidort, Baila. \"The Fifth Commandment\n\". July 29, 2002. Merkos L\u2019Inyonei Chinuch Inc. 2009.[http://lubavitch.com/news/article/2014543/The-Fifth-Commandment.html]\"</ref> \nThroughout the year there are small-scale retreats around the United States such as the Thanksgiving Retreat that was held in Morristown, NJ for High School girls in 2007.<ref>Chabad.org Staff. \"High School Girls Gather for Thanksgiving Retreat in Northern New Jersey\". Nov 30 2007. Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center. 2001-2010.[http://www.chabad.org/news/article_cdo/aid/604347/jewish/High-School-Girls-Gather-for-Thanksgiving-Retreat-in-Northern-New-Jersey.htm]\"</ref> \nThe Snorkel and Study Program, which began in January 2006, is held annually in Key Largo, Florida, and attended by up to 90 female students from campuses around the world.<ref>Lakein, Dvora. \"Into the Depths: Jewish Women Find Self Through Study and Snorkel\". Jan 12 2009. Merkos L\u2019Inyonei Chinuch Inc. [http://lubavitch.com/news/article/2025148/Into-the-Depths-Jewish-Women-Find-Self-Through-Study-and-Snorkel.html]\"</ref> \nThe Un-Camp is geared towards teens, and participants discuss topics such as \"prayer, science, mitzvahs, self-image, relationships, happiness, life and death, the Jewish belief in the Messiah, the soul,\" and more while participating in traditional summer camp activities.<ref>Hecht, Mimi. \"At the Un-Camp, Girls Explore Their Jewish Identities\". July 20, 2007. Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center. 2001-2010. [http://www.chabad.org/news/article_cdo/aid/541843/jewish/At-the-Un-Camp-Girls-Explore-Their-Jewish-Identities.htm]\"</ref>\n\nAnthropologist [[Lynn Davidman]] performed fieldwork for her doctoral dissertation at Bais Chana. The results of her study have been published in her book Tradition in a Rootless World: Women Turn to Orthodox Judaism (UC Press, 1993). Davidman found that the  majority of young women at Bais Chana were there to fill a void in their lives, and were hoping to find an Orthodox husband and begin a family, and that \"strong boundaries\" were established \"between the [Chabad] religious group and the outside.\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zumwalt|first=Rosemary Levy|title=Book Reviews Tradition in a Rootless World|journal=The Journal of American Folklore|date=Summer 1995|volume=108|issue=429|pages=370\u2013372|jstor=541895}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.baischana.org}}\n* http://www.lessonsearned.org/\n{{Chabad}}\n[[Category:Jewish organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chabad schools]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chabad school}}\n'''Bais Chana Women International''' is a [[Chabad]] non-profit organization that works to provide an environment for Jewish girls and women, ages 15 and up and from all backgrounds, to explore Jewish teachings and traditions.<ref>Great Nonprofits, 2010, [http://greatnonprofits.org/reviews/profile2/bais-chana-women-international-inc]\", May 26, 2010</ref><ref>Bais Chana International, 2009, [http://www.baischana.org/content/view/135/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723073011/http://www.baischana.org/content/view/135/ |date=2011-07-23 }}\". June 8, 2010</ref>\n\nBais Chana\u2019s founding was inspired and motivated by  the [[Chabad|Lubavitcher]] Rebbe, Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]]'s support of Jewish education for all women.<ref name=\"bc.org\">Bais Chana International, 2005-2010, {{cite web|url=http://www.baischana.org/content/view/13/124/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504094248/http://www.baischana.org/content/view/13/124/ |archivedate=2010-05-04 }}\", May 26, 2010.</ref> In 1971, its first home was opened in the Twin Cities, Minnesota.<ref name=\"bc.org\" /> In 1991 the organization began diversifying its program to include shorter retreat segments in locations around the world.<ref name=\"bc.org\" /> Women of all ages and little or no formal background in Jewish traditions have taken part in these educational retreats, which include classes, group study, private tutoring and mentoring.<ref name=\"bc.org\"/> The full class schedule explores life as a Jewish woman through hands-on projects such as [[challah]] baking, along with discussions and in-depth study of [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] texts, [[Torah]], prayer, Bible commentary, [[Midrash]], [[Maimonides]], [[Kabbalah]], [[Talmud]] and more. The rotating teaching staff features Bais Chana's co-founder, Rabbi [[Manis Friedman]].<ref name=\"bc.org\" /><ref name=\"bc.org\" /><ref>Philadelphia Jewish Exponent Staff. \"Women Study: A traveling educational program engages women in a deeper perspective of their Jewish tradition\". Rpt on Chabad.org on Mar 5 1999. Chabad-Lubavitch  Media Center. 2001-2010 [http://www.chabad.org/news/article_cdo/aid/409/jewish/Women-Study.htm%20%28this%20originally%20appeared%20in%20a%20Philly%20paper]\"</ref><ref>Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center. 2001-2010. [http://www.chabad.org/search/keyword_cdo/kid/469/jewish/Friedman-Manis.htm]\"</ref> Under the direction of Mrs. Hinda Leah Sharfstein, Bais Chana is now headquartered in New York and has further expanded to include three annual sessions at an array of venues across the United States, including learning retreats for couples, the Snorkel and Study Program, and The Jewish Un-Camp.<ref name=\"bc.org\" /><ref>Olidort, Baila. \"The Fifth Commandment\n\". July 29, 2002. Merkos L\u2019Inyonei Chinuch Inc. 2009.[http://lubavitch.com/news/article/2014543/The-Fifth-Commandment.html]\"</ref> Throughout the year there are small-scale retreats around the United States such as the Thanksgiving Retreat that was held in Morristown, NJ for High School girls in 2007.<ref>Chabad.org Staff. \"High School Girls Gather for Thanksgiving Retreat in Northern New Jersey\". Nov 30 2007. Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center. 2001-2010.[http://www.chabad.org/news/article_cdo/aid/604347/jewish/High-School-Girls-Gather-for-Thanksgiving-Retreat-in-Northern-New-Jersey.htm]\"</ref> The Snorkel and Study Program, which began in January 2006, is held annually in Key Largo, Florida, and attended by up to 90 female students from campuses around the world.<ref>Lakein, Dvora. \"Into the Depths: Jewish Women Find Self Through Study and Snorkel\". Jan 12 2009. Merkos L\u2019Inyonei Chinuch Inc. [http://lubavitch.com/news/article/2025148/Into-the-Depths-Jewish-Women-Find-Self-Through-Study-and-Snorkel.html]\"</ref> The Un-Camp is geared towards teens, and participants discuss topics such as \"prayer, science, mitzvahs, self-image, relationships, happiness, life and death, the Jewish belief in the Messiah, the soul,\" and more while participating in traditional summer camp activities.<ref>Hecht, Mimi. \"At the Un-Camp, Girls Explore Their Jewish Identities\". July 20, 2007. Chabad-Lubavitch Media Center. 2001-2010. [http://www.chabad.org/news/article_cdo/aid/541843/jewish/At-the-Un-Camp-Girls-Explore-Their-Jewish-Identities.htm]\"</ref>\n\nAnthropologist [[Lynn Davidman]] performed fieldwork for her doctoral dissertation at Bais Chana. The results of her study have been published in her book Tradition in a Rootless World: Women Turn to Orthodox Judaism (UC Press, 1993). Davidman found that the  majority of young women at Bais Chana were there to fill a void in their lives, and were hoping to find an Orthodox husband and begin a family, and that \"strong boundaries\" were established \"between the [Chabad] religious group and the outside.\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zumwalt|first=Rosemary Levy|title=Book Reviews Tradition in a Rootless World|journal=The Journal of American Folklore|date=Summer 1995|volume=108|issue=429|pages=370\u2013372|jstor=541895}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.baischana.org}}\n* http://www.lessonsearned.org/\n{{Chabad}}\n[[Category:Jewish organizations based in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bais_Chana_Women_International"}
